<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Derailed train closes three schools, forces evacuation of 16 families </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BINGHAMTON, N.Y. (AP) - Three schools are closed today and 44
people are evacuated from their homes until tomorrow following
derailment of a train carrying hazardous materials.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-nine of the Delaware &AMP; Hudson Railroad train's 82 cars
were derailed in the rural town of Harpursville, 16 miles east of
Binghamton, said state police Sgt. Steven Meyer. Seventeen of those
29 contained hazardous materials.
</P>
<P>
   The derailment happened about 2:45 p.m. Saturday east of Route
79 in Harpursville, parallel to Route 7.
</P>
<P>
   A car carrying methyl chloride began leaking sometime after the
accident and before 9 p.m. Methyl chloride is a colorless,
flammable material that is toxic in high concentrations.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the train's other cars were carrying sulfuric acid and
propane, Meyer said. Soil in the area was found to be contaminated
with nickel hydroxide, which is flammable and toxic as a dust or
fume.
</P>
<P>
   Though there were initial reports of chemical leakage, officials
Sunday said that there had been no leaks and that the evacuations
were precautionary. No injuries were reported.
</P>
<P>
   The railroad tracks are expected to be closed until Thursday
because of damage done to some 2,000 miles of track.
</P>
<P>
   Officials were still investigating the cause of the accident.
The train was going 35 mph, the posted speed limit.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Sabol of Harpursville said the track was lifted on its side
and cars that were ''stacked, tipped and twisted.''
</P>
<P>
   D&AMP;H Railroad officials declined comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
