<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 00:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fla. Arson Suspect To Be Questioned  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- A man seen pedaling away from a burning home
was charged with arson Sunday, and police say they plan to question
him about 40 other suspicious fires that have kept the surrounding
neighborhoods on edge for the past year.
</P>
<P>
   Calvin Reed, 31, who once spent three years in prison for
killing the owner of an empty home he had broken into, was arrested
early Sunday after witnesses saw him ridding away from a vacant
home that had been set ablaze.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are all sorts of mights and could bes that we are
looking into,'' said Tampa Fire Capt. Bill Wade.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, more than three dozen fires have been set in
Tampa Heights and neighboring sections of Ybor City, near downtown.
</P>
<P>
   No one has been injured in the fires, primarily abandoned and
occupied homes, but some were set at night while people were
sleeping inside. Investigators have said they believe the fires
were set by more than one person, but the only other person charged
is believed to be connected to only one blaze.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to second-degree arson, Reed was charged Sunday with
a weapons violation; officers who arrested him said he was carrying
a handgun.
</P>
<P>
   Reed spent three years in prison after he was convicted of the
1986 stabbing of 71-year-old Roger Weaver, who had come to check on
a vacant home he owned. Unknown to Weaver, Reed had been living in
the house for at least two days. He stabbed Weaver when he walked
inside.
</P>
<P>
   After being declared incompetent to stand trial for three years,
Reed was convicted of third-degree murder in 1989. He has been in
and out of prison since, his last release coming in September.
</P>
<P>
   He was being held on $48,500 bond.
</P>
<P>
   The arsons, which started in June of last year, have been a blow
to city leaders who had been pushing to rebuild the neighborhoods
of historic homes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
