<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 01:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> The Government Moves Its Capital  </HEADLINE>
By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two hundred years ago this month, packet ships
from Philadelphia tied up at Lear's Wharf on the Potomac River and
unloaded the baggage of government onto wagons and carts.
</P>
<P>
   More than a decade after work began under the watchful eye of
President Washington, the United States government and its 131
clerks were taking possession of a new capital.
</P>
<P>
   But as members of President John Adams' Cabinet stepped off the
ships to survey the scene, the place was still more construction
site than city.
</P>
<P>
   Cows and pigs wandered freely. Workers' huts and construction
debris littered the grounds of public buildings. Pennsylvania
Avenue was an unpaved, rutted mire clogged with alder brush.
Carpenters and plasterers raced to complete the president's house
at one end of the avenue and one small section of the Capitol at
the other.
</P>
<P>
   The workmen had a deadline. The president and Congress, in
temporary residence at Philadelphia for the last 10 years, would
arrive in November and the work of government would begin, ready or
not.
</P>
<P>
   The full heat and humidity of a Washington summer had yet to
arrive, but political intrigue was already boiling.
</P>
<P>
   The United States in the summer of 1800 was engaged in a bitter
election contest between Adams and Vice President Thomas Jefferson.
Adams, seeking a second term, was the candidate of the Federalists
who favored a strong central government and a manufacturing
economy. Jefferson's Republicans wanted an agrarian America
centered on the states and free of any taint of monarchy.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson and his allies viewed the new federal city with
suspicion and foreboding. They saw hints of royal trappings in the
ceremonially broad avenues and the presidential ''palace.''
</P>
<P>
   The Federalists also were not pleased.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary John Wolcott arrived on July 1 and settled in
at the Treasury Department just east of the president's house.
After hearing the inflated claims of local landowners about the
city's supposedly rosy future he decided he was ''in the company of
crazy people.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Their ignorance of the rest of the world, and their delusions
with respect to their own prospects, are without parallel,''
Wolcott wrote his wife.
</P>
<P>
   As the government's chief financial officer, Wolcott had other
reasons to be appalled.
</P>
<P>
   ''Immense sums have been squandered in buildings which are but
partly finished,'' he complained. ''With great trouble and expense,
much mischief has been done which will be almost impossible to
remedy.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Arnebeck, chronicling the building of the city in his 1991
book, ''Through a Fiery Trial,'' concluded that Wolcott was up to
mischief of his own.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Hamilton, the former Treasury secretary who now pulled
strings from outside the government, asked for inside information
that could be used to embarrass Adams, and perhaps throw the
election to another Federalist candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ''So while ditchers opened a drain down 14th Street, Wolcott,
working in an office close by, became Washington's first leak,''
Arnebeck wrote. Whatever information was provided, Hamilton's
purpose was not achieved.
</P>
<P>
   Housing was scarce. Wolcott said he did not know where members
of Congress would reside, ''unless they will consent to live like
scholars in a college, or monks in a monastery, crowded ten or
twenty in one house ....''
</P>
<P>
   The air of political intrigue added to an unsettled feeling.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have never felt composed or satisfied since I have been
here,'' the State Department's chief clerk said in a letter.
''Everything is mysterious, and everyman's conduct and opinions
inexplicable.'' The clerk resolved to keep his own opinions to
himself.
</P>
<P>
   As the political fever rose, so did the thermometer. ''The heat
here for a few days past has exceeded my experience and unhinged
all my faculties ...,'' James Wilkinson, an Army general, wrote in
mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a hot and sickly summer, supervisors pressed to get as
much work completed as possible. That meant overcoming a shortage
of such necessary supplies as panes of window glass and door locks.
</P>
<P>
   President Adams made an official 10-day inspection in early June
before traveling home to Boston. He was greeted with a 16-gun
salute, observed the carpenters and plasterers at the Capitol and
the executive mansion and paid a call on the recently widowed
Martha Washington at Mount Vernon.
</P>
<P>
   Adams voiced hope for an early end to any lingering reluctance
to move the government to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   As far as he was concerned, the matter was settled.
</P>
<P>
   ''I like the Seat of Government very well, and shall sleep, or
lie awake, next winter in the President's house,'' he wrote his
wife.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE -- Lawrence L. Knutson has reported on the White
House, Congress and the history of Washington for more than 30
years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-12-00 0119 </TRAILER>
