<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 01:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Discontent in City School Districts  </HEADLINE>
By ANJETTA McQUEEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) --The toughest spot in American education is the
helm of a large city school district, say leaders and educators
trying to stop the revolving schoolhouse door.
</P>
<P>
   Such districts, whose students are among the poorest and
neediest, can't hold onto their leaders. They pay high salaries,
launch aggressive searches and even hire non-educators presumably
gifted with business and management acumen, but a big-city
superintendent's tenure averages two years. And many top candidates
try their hand in various systems.
</P>
<P>
   Nine top vacancies, and recent high-profile hires in Los Angeles
and New York, highlight the growing discontent in urban school
systems -- and the challenge of finding the right people to turn
them around.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many boards are asking superintendents to be messiahs,'' said
Michael Casserly, executive director of the Council of the Great
City Schools, a coalition of nearly 60 large districts. ''Urban
districts are a political stew composed of corporations, the
unions, the press and community groups ... they're all fighting
with scarce resources over the one thing they feel most passionate
about: their children.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not realistic that any superintendent could turn around
some of these systems within two years,'' Casserly said.
</P>
<P>
   District of Columbia Superintendent Arlene Ackerman quit last
month after two years.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1970, the capital city has had eight school chiefs.
Ackerman left to head San Francisco's schools after concluding she
couldn't help a 70,000-student district controlled by a mayoral
board, independent auditors and budget committees in the U.S.
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   ''D.C. needs to fix its convoluted and utterly debilitating
governance structure,'' said Casserly. ''Unfortunately, the schools
can't do it because so much is determined elsewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles' superintendent, Ruben Zacarias -- permanently
replaced last week -- was ousted last October after two years.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia's chief, David Hornbeck, who quit last week, stands
out as a six-year veteran. The average tenure for all school
leaders is 7{ years.
</P>
<P>
   Casserly said that 15 years ago, systems were being led by
career educators who stayed five times as long. Today, districts
spend six months to a year on searches for superintendents that can
cost $30,000 to $130,000, he said. Then boards must win public
support for salaries that average $175,000, but can reach $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   The candidate pool is dwindling as the overwhelmingly white and
male population of school leaders retire, Casserly said.
</P>
<P>
   Educators point to other factors, among them increasing pressure
to cut budgets and raise test scores and impatience with career
educators -- leading boards to hire generals, lawyers and
politicians. There's also confusion and conflict about who should
run these schools: the board, the mayor, the state, or in the case
of the District of Columbia, the federal government.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone wants to be involved in some way, shape or form in
reforming the school system,'' said Daniel A. Domenech, who runs
the 154,000-student Fairfax County, Va., system. ''Superintendents
find that in a very relative short period of time, two or three
years, that in fact they can't please all of the masters.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayors in Philadelphia, New York and Detroit have publicly
clashed with school leaders as more politicians seek control over
education, a popular voter issue. And that has taken a toll on
career educators who are not politically astute, some leaders say.
</P>
<P>
   ''You are in a fishbowl,'' said Libby Socorro Gil, Chula Vista,
Calif. schools chief, who was a deputy in Seattle. ''I'm not sure
too many traditional educators are prepared for that kind of
scrutiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Domenech, a school administrator for nearly three decades, said
enough 4-3 board votes on issues near and dear to him taught him to
join the political arena. ''Most of us got into this business
because we care about kids, but this is not a job anyone is
successful in doing unless you have those alliances. On your own
you're dead in the water,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some districts have turned away from educators -- with mixed
results. Retired Gen. John Stanford led the Seattle schools with
charisma and success from 1995 to 1998, when he died of leukemia.
But Julius W. Becton Jr., a former three-star Army general, quit as
D.C. superintendent in 1998 after 16 months.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani eventually agreed to give
Harold Levy, a corporate lawyer with no previous school leadership
experience, a chance to run the 1.1 million student system.
</P>
<P>
   Educators say no one can run a system without resources and
patience.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is not a business putting out widgets,'' said Domenech,
noting that boards must hire enough teachers and fix buildings as
well.
</P>
<P>
   And people must be willing to wait for results, said Michael F.
DiPaola, who trains leaders at the College of William and Mary's
School of Education in Williamsburg, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ''The bottom line is that people are not patient enough to see
it through,'' said DiPaola, a former superintendent. ''When you
change leadership so often, you exacerbate the time it's going to
take.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: The Council of Great City Schools:
http://www.cgcs.org
</P>
</TEXT>
