<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 01:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rwanda Routs Ugandan Forces  </HEADLINE>
By HRVOJE HRANJSKI
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISANGANI, Congo (AP) -- Rwandan troops drove Ugandan forces from
Kisangani Sunday in a fierce seven-hour battle that ended a week of
terrifying, indiscriminate shelling and enabled the United Nations
to deploy between the two armies and prepare for their withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   The bullet-riddled bodies of at least 40 Ugandan soldiers lay
strewn along the gravel road that leads up to the bridge where
Rwandan troops halted the Ugandan push into the city. The stench of
death was everywhere in this Congo River port city, and there was
no water, electricity, food or medicine. But a handful of unarmed
U.N. observers were in place to monitor the cease-fire and for
Kisangani, the worst appeared to be over.
</P>
<P>
   At the bridge, the observers raised the blue U.N. flag and
declared that any further fighting would be considered an act of
aggression against the international community.
</P>
<P>
   This round of fighting, which began on June 5, was the third in
Kisangani between the two armies, who both support rebels trying to
oust Congolese President Laurent Kabila. The city has become a
strategic logistics base for both armies, and disagreements about
the conduct of the 22-month war have increased, as has personal
animosity between senior army commanders on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Exhausted Rwandan soldiers inspected tons of ammunition, guns
and an anti-aircraft battery the Ugandans had left behind.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am not proud of this. But we were fired at. We won because
our soldiers know what they are fighting for,'' Rwandan commander
Col. Karenzi Karake said. ''We are now leaving Kisangani regardless
of Ugandan intentions.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Ugandan capital, Kampala, a senior government official
confirmed that Ugandan forces had withdrawn to Kapalata training
camp, seven miles north of the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   ''We covered ourselves and withdrew because life was becoming
impossible for residents in Kisangani,'' said James Wapakabulo.
</P>
<P>
   Uganda's decision to withdraw demonstrated that Uganda had not
been planning an offensive against Rwanda, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The battle ended early Sunday, when Ugandan army chief of staff
Brig. James Kazini called Karake on a satellite telephone and
requested a cease-fire in order to withdraw, Karake said.
</P>
<P>
   Top army officials from both sides were to meet Monday in
Kampala with a U.N. commander for Congo to work out a speedy
withdrawal of both armies from Kisangani, said Lt. Col. Danilo
Paiva, head of the U.N. observer team.
</P>
<P>
   As an eerie calm settled over the steamy city of 200,000,
trembling residents who live near the site where Rwandan troops
halted the Ugandans ventured out for the first time in a week.
</P>
<P>
   Marcel Thambwe, 30, was dumbfounded at the extent of the
destruction. Not a single dwelling, neither houses nor apartment
buildings, escaped damage.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why? This has no purpose,'' Thambwe said. ''We just want them
out of here. Both Rwandans and Ugandans. Bring over the United
Nations and stop this destruction. Please.''
</P>
<P>
   U.N. observers said at least 6,000 shells had rained down on
Kisangani since fighting broke out last Monday. The Red Cross had
put the civilian death toll at 150 with 1,114 injured. It was
obvious the number would rise as people were discovered in the
rubble of their homes and bodies were collected from the streets.
</P>
<P>
   Three children died and one was wounded Sunday when they were
playing with unexploded hand grenades, said Alexander Liebeskind of
the Red Cross. As many as 20,000 Congolese have been displaced, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Two men pushed exhausted relatives in wheelbarrows through
streets littered with bodies, spent cartridges and artillery
shells. Women in one house wailed over their five dead children
killed by a mortar that exploded at the entrance of a school.
Everyone begged for water and food.
</P>
<P>
   Church bells pealed from the twin spires of the 101-year-old
Roman Catholic cathedral, which sustained heavy damage from
shelling. Congolese priests said Mass to a few dozen faithful who
prayed with neither altar nor pews.
</P>
<P>
   People washed and fetched water in the chocolate brown Congo,
while others took to dugout canoes to finally reach homes on the
south bank of the mighty river.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
