<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 01:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Shots Fired at Fiji Leader  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE CORDER
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- Soldiers opened fire Monday on a car carrying
coup leader George Speight, shooting it full of holes but missing
Speight, who holds 31 people hostage in Fiji's parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Rebel spokesman Joe Nata said it was ''a deliberate effort by
the military to kill George Speight. We are treating it as an
assassination attempt.''
</P>
<P>
   An army spokesman blamed bad judgment by soldiers at a
checkpoint that Speight's car sped through. Lt. Col. Filipo
Tarakinikini insisted the shooting did not represent an escalation
of the conflict, and said the soldiers would be disciplined for
using excessive force.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers shot at Speight's car as he was returning from a
meeting in the vice president's house.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am alive and well,'' Speight told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Speight's car, a dark green Hyundai sedan, was peppered with at
least two bullet holes, one in the right rear passenger door and
one in the right rear panel. Both rear passenger windows were
smashed.
</P>
<P>
   Tarakinikini said Speight's car was one of two that sped through
a military roadblock. Soldiers first fired warning shots in the
air, then fired at Speight's car when the vehicles failed to stop.
Tarakinikini said about 20 shots were fired.
</P>
<P>
   The other car stopped, and soldiers arrested the rebels inside.
Officials quickly freed them after the rebels phoned and threatened
the hostages could otherwise be harmed, a military statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Nata said Speight was on his way back from drinking tea with a
Methodist church leader. Nata assured the public the rebels would
not retaliate even though Speight's supporters inside parliament
''wanted to go out and kill everything in front of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Speight had not previously been attacked since he seized his
hostages May 19, although he has ventured out of the parliamentary
compound several times.
</P>
<P>
   The martial law regime of Commodore Frank Bainimarama, which
took control of Fiji 10 days into the crisis, had previously
pledged it would not try to use force and free the hostages,
including deposed Prime Minister Mahendra Chaudhry.
</P>
<P>
   Speight, in turn, had said he would not harm his hostages if the
military did not attack the compound that has become a camp full of
Speight supporters.
</P>
<P>
   Speight's ventures outside had included trips to the military
barracks for negotiations with Bainimarama that broke down last
week when the military said it would entertain no more demands from
Speight.
</P>
<P>
   Speight claims to be acting on behalf of Fiji's indigenous
majority in his fight for a new government system that
discriminates against the ethnic Indian minority by denying them
political power. Chaudhry last year became the first ethnic Indian
to become Fiji's prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   The military had previously taken steps that met a number of
Speight's demands, including scrapping Fiji's 1997 constitution
that gave Indians greater rights -- and removing the president.
</P>
<P>
   Bainimarama also offered amnesty to Speight and his armed gang
in exchange for release of the hostages and surrender of their
weapons, but the crisis has been in a standoff over disagreements
over the form of Fiji's next government.
</P>
<P>
   The military has ruled out any role by Speight or his supporters
in a new government.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Monday, police halted a march that had been called to
protest Speight's seizure of the hostages and they arrested its
organizer, the son of one of the hostages, because he had no permit
for the march. Witnesses said only a handful of people had arrived
in the western town of Lautoka to take part.
</P>
<P>
   Two days earlier, a mob of Speight supporters armed with
sugarcane-cutting knives torched a seaside restaurant. There were
no injuries, and the violent crowd did not confront the army,
Tarakinikini said.
</P>
<P>
   Already this week, rebels have exchanged warning shots with the
army and beaten up a policeman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
