<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 2 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, June 12, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Shots Fired at Fiji Rebel Leader
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SUVA, Fiji (AP) -- Soldiers opened fire Monday on a car carrying coup leader
George Speight, shooting it full of holes but missing Speight, who holds 31
people hostage in Fiji's parliament. Rebel spokesman Joe Nata said it was ''a
deliberate effort by the military to kill George Speight. We are treating it as
an assassination attempt.'' An army spokesman blamed bad judgment by soldiers at
a checkpoint that Speight's car sped through. Lt. Col. Filipo Tarakinikini
insisted the shooting did not represent an escalation of the conflict, and said
the soldiers would be disciplined for using excessive force.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Park Service Set 'Prescribed Fires'
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Until last month, the National Park Service had been
sharply increasing the number of fires set to clear brush and rehabilitate
landscapes, tripling the area burned in just four years. That changed when a
fire set at Bandelier National Monument got out of control, leading to an
inferno that destroyed more than 200 homes in Los Alamos, N.M., and caused
hundreds of millions of dollars in damage. Interior Secretary Bruce Babbitt
halted all ''prescribed fires'' by the Park Service in the West indefinitely,
saying an investigation found ''serious systemic problems in the way the Park
Service conducts prescribed burns.''
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Teamsters Strike at Pepsi Plant
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS (AP) -- More than 400 Teamsters went on strike Sunday night at
the Pepsi bottling plant that serves this metropolitan area, and union members
could strike as early as Monday at a nearby Coca-Cola plant, union officials
said. Teamsters at the Midwest Coca-Cola Bottling plant in Eagan voted to reject
the company's latest contract offer Sunday night. Mediation was due to resume
Monday, but Yoswa said a strike could be called as early as Monday for the
plant's more than 550 Teamsters.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Iraq Asks UN For Money For Supplies
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) -- Iraq asked the United Nations on Sunday to free up $400
million from the surplus in an escrow account to purchase humanitarian supplies
for the Iraqi people. The request came in a letter from Foreign Minister
Mohammed Saeed al-Sahhaf to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan and was carried by
the official Iraqi News Agency. The oil-for-food program allows Iraq to
circumvent U.N. economic sanctions and sell oil under U.N. supervision.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Study: Most Death Row Cases Flawed
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two-thirds of death penalty cases that were appealed from
1973 through 1995 were successful, report researchers who contend the nation's
capital punishment system is ''collapsing under the weight of its own
mistakes.'' A study of 4,578 appeals during those years showed that most cases
''are so seriously flawed that they have to be done over again,'' said Columbia
University law professor James Liebman, the lead author. Earlier this year,
Republican Gov. George Ryan of Illinois imposed a moratorium on capital
punishment in his state after 13 death row inmates were exonerated.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Web Attracts Younger News Audience
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Key segments of the nation's news audience, particularly
younger and better-educated Americans, and those seeking financial information,
are turning increasingly to the Internet, says a new poll on media trends. The
Web's rapid growth as a source for news continues a splintering of that audience
among the Internet, cable and broadcast television, and print publications. A
third of the public now goes online for news at least once a week, compared to a
fifth two years ago, according to a Pew Research poll.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Attack Reported on Solomon Islands
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   HONIARA, Solomon Islands (AP) -- A new group of militants gunned down a man
Sunday in the Solomon Islands, officials said, a killing that diplomats feared
could end a fragile cease-fire and spark another cycle of revenge attacks in the
South Pacific nation. The shooting came as a new wave of foreign tourists and
workers, many pushing carts piled high with luggage, lined up at the airport in
the capital, Honiara to be evacuated. Despite the evacuations, Honiara appeared
relatively calm.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Rise
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks edged higher Monday morning in light trading. The
Nikkei gained 58.23 points to 16,920.14 at the end of the morning session.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Pacers Win Game 3 in NBA Finals
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Reggie Miller scored 31 points, Jalen Rose added 21 and
a number of timely shots as the Indiana Pacers defeated the Los Angeles Lakers
100-91 Sunday. Indiana went ahead by as many as 18 points and held off the
Lakers' rally in the fourth to cut their deficit to 2-1 in the series. Game 4 is
Wednesday night at Indiana.
</P>
