<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court To Hear Alaska Waters Dispute  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD CARELLI
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court agreed Monday to referee a
dispute over ownership and control of marine waters and submerged
lands across Southeast Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is whether Alaska or the federal government has title
to areas within the Tongass National Forest and the Glacier Bay
National Park and Preserve.
</P>
<P>
   Alaska also is asking the court to decide who holds the title to
submerged lands along the Alexander Archipelago, a group of over
1,000 islands over an area nearly 600 miles long and 100 miles wide
with more than 13,000 miles of shoreline.
</P>
<P>
   Holding title would give the state the right to regulate
activities in the water above those submerged lands, notably
commercial fishing.
</P>
<P>
   The justices are allowing Alaska to ''sue'' the federal
government in the Supreme Court without first having the dispute
heard in some lower court. The Constitution gives the court such
''original jurisdiction'' in certain cases.
</P>
<P>
   The submerged lands issue took on new prominence after the
National Park Service decided to phase out commercial fishing in
the waters of Glacier Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's time to resolve, once and for all, the issue of where
federal jurisdiction ends and state jurisdiction begins in
Southeast Alaska,'' Gov. Tony Knowles said when the state sought
Supreme Court help in November. ''The Park Service's phaseout of
commercial fishing in Glacier Bay is just one of many actions taken
over the years that restrict access and activities on state
waters.''
</P>
<P>
   In the appeal acted on Monday, the state's lawyers said, ''The
marine waters of Southeast Alaska are vitally important to the 33
coastal communities and numerous tiny settlements there ... The
sounds, straits, canals, channels and narrows of Southeast Alaska --
known collectively as the Inside Passage -- form its roads.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton administration lawyers, who disagree with the state's
claims, told the justices they did not oppose having them resolve
the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Such cases can take years to resolve. The justices typically
appoint a ''special master'' to conduct hearings and make
recommendations. Monday's brief order gave Justice Department
lawyers 60 days to file a formal response to Alaska's complaint, a
preliminary step to either appointing a special master or
conducting oral arguments.
</P>
<P>
   The case is Alaska vs. U.S., 128 Original.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
