<HEADLINE> Stocks Mixed in Early Trading  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks were mixed in early trading today after a
pair of technology companies released vastly different profit
forecasts, leading investors to question the outlook for corporate
earnings in the current quarter.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was up 16.26 at 10,630.32.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were mixed. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was up 5.77 at 1,462.72, and the Nasdaq composite index was
down 8.87 at 3,865.97.
</P>
<P>
   Corning rose $16 to $228. The company said it anticipates
earnings for the second quarter to be 78 cents to 80 cents a share,
well above analysts' estimates of 69 cents a share. Corning expects
profits to come in about 50 percent above last year's
second-quarter totals.
</P>
<P>
   But Corning's rosy forecast was tempered by a warning from
Citrix Systems Inc., a maker of computer network products that said
its earnings will miss estimates in the coming quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Citrix said expansion of its core business in large enterprise
accounts is taking place slower than expected. Its shares plunged
$16.75 to $24.438.
</P>
<P>
   With three weeks remaining in the second quarter, companies are
just beginning the ''preannouncement'' period, in which companies
give Wall Street advance notice of any disappointments or positive
surprises. The second quarter is generally expected to be a strong
one, but with interest rates on the rise, analysts expect investors
to harshly punish any company that appears to be losing momentum.
</P>
<P>
   Rising interest rates can hurt corporate profits by making it
more expensive to borrow money to finance growth.
</P>
<P>
   Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 4-to-3 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 96.4 million shares,
well behind Friday's quiet pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 1.26 to 521.80.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.7 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 0.6 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.3 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up
0.4 percent.
</P>
