<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 10:30 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DuPont Appeal Rejected by Court  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD CARELLI
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- John DuPont, the heir to a family chemical
fortune convicted in 1997 as a mentally ill murderer, lost a
Supreme Court appeal Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The justices, without comment, rejected a challenge to a
Pennsylvania law that allowed a jury in Media, Pa., to find DuPont
guilty of third-degree murder but mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont is serving a prison sentence of 13 to 30 years for the
1996 shooting death of Olympic gold medal-winning wrestler David
Schultz.
</P>
<P>
   He had pleaded insanity. State prosecutors had sought a
first-degree murder conviction.
</P>
<P>
   DuPont's lawyer, Harvard law professor Alan Dershowitz, said the
Pennsylvania law ''gives rise to an unacceptably high risk'' that
someone legally insane, and therefore not subject to punishment,
will be found to be mentally ill but guilty.
</P>
<P>
   That risk violated DuPont's constitutionally protected rights of
due process and equal protection and subjected him to cruel and
unusual punishment, the appeal said. It also raised other issues.
</P>
<P>
   Pennsylvania prosecutors waived their right to respond to the
appeal, and the nation's highest court did not request a response
brief from the state before taking Monday's action.
</P>
<P>
   A dozen other states have enacted laws that allow juries to find
mentally disturbed defendants guilty but mentally ill. Those laws
add a fourth option to the traditional alternative verdicts of
guilty, not guilty and not guilty by reason of insanity in cases in
which defendants plead insanity.
</P>
<P>
   The other states are Alaska, Delaware, Georgia, Illinois,
Indiana, Kentucky, Michigan, Nevada, New Mexico, South Carolina,
South Dakota and Utah, according to DuPont's appeal.
</P>
<P>
   But Pennsylvania's 1982 law is unique, the appeal contended,
because the legal standard for finding someone legally insane is
the same as the one for finding him guilty but mentally ill.
</P>
<P>
   ''A jury permitted to choose between the two alternatives is
deciding a defendant's fate by the flip of a coin,'' the appeal
said, adding that juries end up being encouraged to choose between
defendants who are ''sick rather than bad'' and those who are
''both bad and sick.''
</P>
<P>
   '''Bad' is a moral or ethical judgment, not a legal standard,
and it is irrelevant to assessing a defendant's mental state,'' the
appeal said.
</P>
<P>
   A state appeals court rejected that argument last year, and the
Pennsylvania Supreme Court refused to hear DuPont's ensuing appeal
in January.
</P>
<P>
   The case is DuPont vs. Pennsylvania, 99-1809.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-12-00 1030 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
