<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Rules Against Bank Robber  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE ASSEO
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- People charged under a federal bank robbery
law are not entitled to have the jury consider whether they
committed the lesser crime of bank larceny, the Supreme Court said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Ruling 5-4 in a New Jersey case, the justices said the federal
larceny law contains several elements that are not part of the
robbery law, and therefore larceny cannot be considered a ''lesser
included offense.''
</P>
<P>
   Floyd J. Carter had argued that the jury should have a choice of
convicting him of larceny, which does not involve the use of force,
violence or intimidation as robbery does.
</P>
<P>
   However, Justice Clarence Thomas wrote for the court that
larceny cannot be considered a lesser offense of bank robbery.
Thomas said the larceny law requires proof of three elements not
included in robbery: intent to steal, property worth more than
$1,000, and proof that the defendant ''takes and carries away'' the
property.
</P>
<P>
   The robbery law requires no proof of the defendant's intent, the
value of the property or that it is carried away, Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   The justices upheld a federal appeals court decision that
affirmed the bank robbery conviction of Carter, who was charged
after he walked into the Collective Savings Bank in Hamilton, N.J.,
in September 1997, unarmed and wearing a ski mask.
</P>
<P>
   Police said he jumped over the counter to an unoccupied teller
station and emptied several drawers of cash, getting away with
about $16,000.
</P>
<P>
   As he went out the door, he told employees, ''Don't bother
following me, I run fast.'' He was arrested later that day.
</P>
<P>
   A jury convicted Carter of bank robbery after the trial judge
refused to let jurors consider the lesser offense of bank larceny.
He was sentenced to 17 years and 11 months.
</P>
<P>
   The 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals upheld his conviction and
sentence, disagreeing with other federal appeals courts that had
allowed jurors to consider larceny as a lesser offense.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court said the 3rd Circuit court was correct.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas' opinion was joined by Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist
and Justices Sandra Day O'Connor, Antonin Scalia and Anthony M.
Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Dissenting were Justices Ruth Bader Ginsburg, John Paul Stevens,
David H. Souter and Stephen G. Breyer.
</P>
<P>
   Writing for the four, Ginsburg said the majority had made a
''woodenly literal'' interpretation of the law. Traditionally, she
said, ''robbery meant larceny plus force, violence or putting in
fear'' and larceny was considered a lesser offense of robbery.
</P>
<P>
   ''Congress, I conclude, did not depart from that traditional
understanding'' in making robbery and larceny federal crimes,
Ginsburg said.
</P>
<P>
   The case is Carter vs. U.S., 99-5716.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For current Supreme Court decisions:
http://www.supremecourtus.gov or
http://supct.law.cornell.edu/supct/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-12-00 1132 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000612.0040 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 12:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Worker Benefit Plans Can Sue Brokers  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD CARELLI
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Employee benefit plans can sue brokers and
others who provide services for their roles in money-losing deals
on grounds that certain transactions are barred by a federal
pension-protecting law, the Supreme Court ruled Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The unanimous decision means Ameritech Corp. and its pension
plan trustee, Harris Trust and Savings Bank, can continue trying to
recover some $20 million lost in a deal with Salomon Brothers Smith
Barney Inc., a stock brokerage that is now part of Citigroup Inc.
</P>
<P>
   At issue were provisions in the federal Employee Retirement
Income and Security Act (ERISA) that bar anyone with a legal duty
to an employee benefit plan -- what lawyers call a fiduciary -- from
engaging in certain transactions with a ''party in interest,'' or
someone the fiduciary might favor at the expense of the plan's
beneficiaries.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Clarence Thomas wrote for the court that the provisions
allow such parties in interest to be sued by the plan even though
they are not fiduciaries of the plan.
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1980s, Salomon sold $21 million worth of interests
in a financial deal involving two motel chains to Ameritech's
pension plan. The plan lost nearly all of its investment in the
deal after the motel chains failed.
</P>
<P>
   Ameritech and the bank that administers its pension plan sued.
Among other things, the lawsuit invoked ERISA and alleged that the
sale had been unfair and a ''prohibited transaction'' under that
law.
</P>
<P>
   Salomon contended it could not be sued under ERISA because it,
unlike Harris Trust and Savings Bank, owed no fiduciary duty to the
pension plan. The 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals agreed with
Salomon and dismissed the case. That left the pension plan with
only one option -- sue its trustee for engaging in the deal.
</P>
<P>
   But six other federal appeals courts had allowed such lawsuits
even in the absence of a fiduciary duty.
</P>
<P>
   Monday's decision sided with those interpretations of ERISA and
reinstated Ameritech's lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   The case is Harris Trust and Savings Bank vs. Salomon Smith
Barney, 99-579.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For the decision:
http://supct.law.cornell.edu/supct/ Click on ''this month's
decisions'' or http://www.supremecourtus.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-12-00 1203 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000612.0041 </DOCNO>
