<DOCNO> APW20000612.0059 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 15:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lott Won't Rush Vote on China Trade  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott said Monday
that he won't speed a vote on the China trade bill, despite pleas
by corporate America and the Clinton administration for quick
action.
</P>
<P>
   ''If we rush to it we could take something that probably is
going to pass overwhelmingly and get it tangled up in a way that
would be counterproductive,'' the Mississippi Republican told
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   As do most Republicans, Lott backs the legislation to grant
China permanent normal trading benefits to accompany its expected
entry into the World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   But Lott said it needs a full airing -- with members given the
chance to offer amendments if they so desire.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Lott indicated the Senate must give higher priority
to spending bills needed to keep the government in operation in the
new fiscal year, which begins Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   China-trade bill supporters have sought to parlay the
unexpectedly strong 40-vote margin of support in the House last
month into fast Senate approval -- even if it means accepting the
House version and not seeking to amend it further.
</P>
<P>
   The House added amendments to set up a commission to monitor
human rights in China and a process to protect U.S. industries from
surges in low-price Chinese imports.
</P>
<P>
   Sponsors hope to get the measure passed before the Fourth of
July, fearful that the longer the delay, the more the measure will
get snarled in election politics.
</P>
<P>
   Both major-party presidential candidates support the bill. But
it is being strongly opposed by organized labor, a key Democratic
constituency, and that could weigh in congressional races in
November.
</P>
<P>
   Lott said he believes the measure will ultimately pass the
Senate and that things need to run their normal course.
</P>
<P>
   Amendments have been proposed from both ends of the political
spectrum.
</P>
<P>
   And Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., said he wants to pursue
legislation he is sponsoring with Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J.,
to set up a process for monitoring China's role in the
proliferation of nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson said he either wants a separate vote or he'll push it
as an amendment to the China trade bill.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's got a very strong proposal that's going to have to be
considered,'' Lott said Monday. ''And I'm going to work with him
and others to decide how that will be carried out.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Senate Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., told
reporters that, while he supports the right of senators ''to
express themselves and to offer amendments,'' he planned to oppose
all of them in hopes of speeding the bill along.
</P>
<P>
   Daschle said there was ''broad based support'' for the bill in
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ''And the clearer we can send the message that we want to get on
with our new trading relationship with China, we ought to do that.
I'd prefer to do that before the Fourth of July. There's no reason
why we should wait.''
</P>
<P>
   The House passed the bill 237 to 197 on May 24.
</P>
<P>
   On a related subject, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright told
reporters that the United States has ''real concerns'' about
Israel's proposed sale of radar technology to China. But, she
added, ''we will oppose any effort on Capitol Hill'' to try to link
the sale to U.S. assistance to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Some conservative House Republicans have suggested such a
linkage.
</P>
<P>
   Israel is building a plane for China and equipping it with the
U.S.-developed PHALCON airborne early warning radar system at a
cost of $250 million.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The China trade bills are H.R. 4444 and S. 2277
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: White House site: http://www.chinapntr.gov
</P>
<P>
   AFL-CIO site: http://www.aflcio.org/publ/press2000/pr0222.htm
</P>
