<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentine Leader Touts Economy Plan  </HEADLINE>
By IAN JAMES
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Argentina's president defended his economic plan
of higher taxes and spending cuts Monday, saying that despite
recent public protests, the measures are helping to revitalize his
country's economy.
</P>
<P>
   President Fernando De la Rua used his stop in New York on his
first official visit to the United States to urge a group of about
300 financial and business leaders to steer investments toward
Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at a breakfast held by the Americas Society, the
Argentine leader acknowledged the unpopularity of lowering the
budget deficit by raising taxes and cutting state workers'
salaries.
</P>
<P>
   ''It always carries a political cost, but one must have the
courage to assume the political costs if one wants to take a
country forward,'' he said. ''If I didn't take the necessary
measures, it would again provoke in the country the crisis we have
to get away from. And we are getting away from the problems.''
</P>
<P>
   With Argentina's unemployment rate at 14 percent, however, many
of the country's people are losing patience. Hundreds of thousands
of workers across Argentina staged a national strike Friday to
protest De la Rua's economic policies, closing many businesses and
halting buses and trains.
</P>
<P>
   De la Rua told his listeners in a hotel conference room that he
hoped they would not take the images of the strike as representing
the situation in Argentina.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have shown some images of some people in the street, of
burned tires. That wasn't the situation in the country. It could
have been that way in two or three places,'' he said. ''But in
general, the unions called a strike that occurred in a peaceful
fashion, and after the strike, what remains open is the path of
dialogue and prudent discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   De la Rua, who took office in December, drew applause when he
reaffirmed his staunch support for keeping the value of the
country's currency, the peso, pegged to the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
   He showed the audience an economic report, lifting the pages
into the air to display graphs showing improvement -- in industrial
production, supermarket sales and other measures.
</P>
<P>
   ''With these facts, I only want to tell you that things are
getting better,'' De la Rua said. ''I'm convinced that my country
has what it takes to successfully face the challenges of this new
century.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week, De la Rua said in an interview with The Associated
Press that his economic advisers had scaled back the country's
growth target for the year from 4 percent to 3.5 percent, or
perhaps less.
</P>
<P>
   But during his speech Monday, he emphasized that Argentina's
exports have grown, together with the neighboring economies of
Chile, Uruguay and Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest round of government cutbacks last month, De la Rua
ordered cuts in state salaries to trim a $7.1 billion deficit by
$2.5 billion this year.
</P>
<P>
   The cost-cutting measures help Argentina maintain access to
loans from the International Monetary Fund if needed. But De la Rua
said the IMF is not the force behind his economic program.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some say that our program is demanded by the fund. That's not
so. We are complying with the national law of fiscal
responsibility, and I'm convinced that we're going to reach our
goals.''
</P>
<P>
   He said creating new jobs is a priority. And he urged the
financiers to invest in Argentine tourism, mining and
telecommunications, saying his country's economy offers ''immense
possibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, De la Rua is to visit Washington, where he plans to
meet President Clinton and publicly seek forgiveness for his
country's role in providing sanctuary to Nazis after World War II.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-12-00 1541 </TRAILER>
