<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Political Battle Turns Nasty  </HEADLINE>
By KARIN LAUB
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- A religious Israeli government minister
compares a critical Cabinet colleague to the Nazis, and a Jewish
settler suggests parallels between Adolf Hitler's regime and Prime
Minister Ehud Barak's government.
</P>
<P>
   A flurry of epithets this week invoking the Holocaust was met by
widespread condemnation in a country built on the ashes of the Nazi
genocide.
</P>
<P>
   However, it also laid bare the deep animosities -- between
religious and secular, hawks and doves -- that Barak will have to
bridge to put together a new coalition stable enough to ratify a
future Israeli-Palestinian peace agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are deeply divided on basic values, and the culture war
that has been going on for a number of years has reached a very
serious level,'' said author Tom Segev, who has written on the
impact of the Holocaust on Israeli society.
</P>
<P>
   Barak is trying to rebuild his coalition after three rebellious
parties voted last week with the opposition in support of a bill
calling for early elections. The prime minister has said he would
not tolerate such behavior in the future, but has backed down from
threats to throw out the three renegade factions for good.
</P>
<P>
   He has until July, when the bill is up for the next vote, to put
together a new coalition. Barak needs at least one of the parties
to return, preferably the ultra-Orthodox Shas faction whose dispute
with the prime minister is over money, not ideology.
</P>
<P>
   If he fails, he will have to rely on a coalition of 52 dovish
and secular lawmakers and hope that on crucial peace issues, he
will win the outside support of 10 Arab legislators for a narrow
majority of 62 in the 120-seat parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's courtship of Shas was complicated when Health Minister
Shlomo Ben-Izri, a leading figure in the party, accused another
senior coalition member, Education Minister Yossi Sarid of the
secular Meretz party, of persecuting Shas.
</P>
<P>
   Sarid has been sharply critical of Shas' attempts to extract
more state funding for its bankrupt school system by threatening to
leave the coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feel frustrated by the persecution we are experiencing,
among others by Sarid,'' Ben-Izri said. ''They are using methods
against us that remind me of the Nazi propaganda, the way it was
used then against the Jews. They (the Nazis) claimed the Jews were
blackmailers trying to extract money.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben-Izri also lashed out at Tommy Lapid, leader of the secular
Shinui party who has said he would not join the coalition as long
as Shas is part of it. The health minister said Lapid, a
sharp-tongued former TV talk show star and Holocaust survivor, was
a ''Super Haider,'' a reference to the Austrian far-right leader,
Joerg Haider.
</P>
<P>
   In a televised confrontation with his nemesis on Monday night,
Ben-Izri told Lapid that his attacks on Shas may ultimately foment
a ''civil war.''
</P>
<P>
   A day earlier, Jewish settlers protesting the government's
declared willingness to uproot tens of thousands of West Bank
settlers in a final peace agreement with the Palestinians drew a
parallel between the Barak coalition and the Nazi regime.
</P>
<P>
   At a rally outside Barak's home, one of the speakers read his
adaptation of famous words by German pastor Martin Niemoeller, who
wrote that no one was left to speak out against his imprisonment in
a Nazi concentration camp because he had not protested when Jews,
Communists and others were seized by Hitler's gendarmes.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the beginning, they expelled the settlers, and I didn't
speak out because I wasn't a settler,'' the speaker read at
Sunday's rally. ''Then they took the ultra-Orthodox, and I didn't
speak out because I wasn't ultra-Orthodox.''
</P>
<P>
   Settler activist Daniella Weiss defended the analogy, saying all
means were permissible to prevent the handover of parts of the
biblical Land of Israel to the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ''The rest are games by leftists and bleeding-heart liberals,''
said Weiss, shrugging off concerns that hurtful words could bring
back the divisive political climate that led to the November 1995
assassination of Yitzhak Rabin by an ultranationalist Jew.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-12-00 1604 </TRAILER>
