<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Assad's Brother To Challenge Nephew  </HEADLINE>
By SAM F. GHATTAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) -- The estranged brother of late Syrian
President Hafez Assad hinted Monday he will work to overthrow the
new government, nearly certain to be headed by Assad's son and
chosen successor, Bashar Assad.
</P>
<P>
   ''There will be a new corrective movement for a new course
covering all political, social and economic levels,'' the brother,
Rifaat Assad, said in a televised statement to the Syrian people.
</P>
<P>
   By referring to a ''corrective movement,'' Rifaat was borrowing
terminology used to refer to Hafez Assad's 1970 takeover of Syria
in a bloodless coup. The late president, who was then Syria's
defense minister, declared the coup was to correct the course of
the ruling Arab Baath Socialist Party, which he said had deviated
from its true objectives.
</P>
<P>
   Rifaat, a former Syrian vice president, has been exiled since
1984. Earlier Monday, a spokesman for Rifaat said he wants to bring
about change in Syria through peaceful means.
</P>
<P>
   ''Dr. Rifaat stresses peaceful action and refraining from
spilling blood, and does not want Syria to drown in blood. But he
believes that legitimacy will prevail in a rightful way,''
Al-Hareth Al-Khair told The Associated Press in a telephone
interview from Rifaat's home in exile in Marbella, Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Al-Khair said Rifaat plans to return to Syria but for now is
still in Europe. He would not say where.
</P>
<P>
   Rifaat's challenge came as Bashar Assad was making his way to
the top of Syria's political hierarchy. In swift steps after
President Assad's death Saturday, the Syrian Parliament lowered the
age of presidential eligibility to match Bashar's age, the ruling
Baath Party nominated him for the presidency and the government
named him commander of the armed forces.
</P>
<P>
   The first public indication that Rifaat was considered a threat
to Bashar surfaced earlier Monday, when a newspaper reported that
Rifaat would not be allowed to return to Syria. The Al-Hayat daily
quoted an unidentified senior Syrian official as saying orders had
been issued to arrest Rifaat should he show up in the country.
</P>
<P>
   In Lebanon, where 30,000 Syrian troops are stationed, witnesses
reported increased security checks at Beirut International Airport
and at seaports. Security officials speaking on condition of
anonymity said Syrian agents were on the lookout for Rifaat in case
he tried to sneak through the porous Lebanese border.
</P>
<P>
   Rifaat Assad was a feared and effective enforcer of President
Assad's wishes during much of his 30-year rule. In 1982, he and his
crack army units crushed a Muslim fundamentalist uprising in the
northern city of Hama, leveling a huge swath of the city and
reportedly killing 10,000 to 20,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   But a year later, as the president lay in a hospital
recuperating from a heart attack, Rifaat's tanks began maneuvering
on the streets of the capital, Damascus, in what was seen as an
attempted coup.
</P>
<P>
   Rifaat spent most of the next few years in exile. He returned to
Syria for his mother's funeral in 1992, and he was last seen at a
public event in Syria in 1994 at the funeral of Basil Assad, the
president's eldest son, who died in a traffic crash.
</P>
<P>
   In his statement Monday, the 63-year-old Rifaat said he wants to
change the way autocratic Syria has been governed for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ''Freedom and democracy will be established in Syria. The
citizen will play his role in building the nation and choosing his
representatives in Syria,'' Rifaat said in the statement read on
Arab News Network, a London-based satellite television station
owned by Rifaat's son, Sawmar.
</P>
<P>
   He criticized the speed of developments in Damascus that cleared
the way for Bashar's rise.
</P>
<P>
   ''You have left a sudden and tragic vacuum which some believed
they could fill, underestimating the issue of your succession and
downplaying the enormity of responsibility,'' he said, addressing
the late president.
</P>
<P>
   There was no official word from Syria on measures against
Rifaat. But Lt. Gen. Mustafa Tlass, the longtime defense minister
and deputy armed forces chief, warned that the ruling Baath Party
and the military back Bashar against any potential threat.
</P>
<P>
   ''We will always be on his side. ... Let no one try to drive a
wedge in this united front,'' he told Lebanon's Future television
station.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-12-00 1633 </TRAILER>
