<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 16:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Journalists Still Face Old Terrors  </HEADLINE>
By HAROLD OLMOS
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- The message on a scrap of paper
was written with a fractured hand but a still-unbroken spirit. It
read simply: ''Help me before it is too late.''
</P>
<P>
   The writer, Syrian journalist Nizar Nayouf, has been jailed
since 1992 for writing poems that angered his country's leaders and
for refusing to turn down international awards honoring his cause
and his courage.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the World Association of Newspapers added to that
list by awarding Nayouf the Freedom Gold Pen award in absentia.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unfortunately, he is not here. Maybe one day,'' said Ruth de
Aquino, the Brazilian editor of the Rio de Janeiro daily O Dia and
president of the World Editors Forum.
</P>
<P>
   As 1,400 publishers and journalists gathered to discuss issues
such as the impact of the Internet on newspapers, many members of
the press like Nayouf still face centuries-old problems of
censorship, repression and terror.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, at least 71 members of the media were killed while on
the job, many victims of ''cold-blooded assassination,'' said Bengt
Braun of Sweden, association president. Worldwide, 124 journalists
in 24 countries are serving long prison terms.
</P>
<P>
   ''Murder is the ultimate form of censorship,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A black-and-white picture of Nayouf projected behind her, de
Aquino quoted Nayouf as saying he was being held in ''one of the
most savage, bloody, criminal and secretive places in the world,''
where three to five people die from torture every day.
</P>
<P>
   It is a ''cemetery of living creatures,'' she quoted Nayouf, 27,
as saying.
</P>
<P>
   Among the abuses he described were dogs urinating on him and
being held on tiptoe in a simulated crucifixion for three hours a
day for a month. His captors tried to assassinate him three times,
once by placing arsenic in his food, and he was denied medical
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Nayouf managed to smuggle out written messages to let the world
know of his condition, and one of the last was a cry for help, de
Aquino said.
</P>
<P>
   ''His torturers broke a finger of his right hand. Still he
managed to write,'' she said. ''He has become the voice of
democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Colombian journalist Francisco Santos Calderon, editor of the
Bogota daily El Tiempo, faced a similar ordeal. He was kidnapped
for eight months and freed in 1991. After learning that hit men had
been paid to kill him, he fled into exile in the United States and
Spain.
</P>
<P>
   Now writing for his newspaper via e-mail from Miami, Santos told
conference members of the terror journalists in his country often
face.
</P>
<P>
   ''A couple of weeks ago, a Colombian journalist went to an
appointment with a paramilitary agent. She was kidnapped, tortured
and abandoned 60 miles to the southwest of Bogota,'' he said Monday
at the opening session of the three-day meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ''The message for her and all journalists was clear: We can
kidnap and kill you, but this time we will not,'' Santos said.
</P>
<P>
   Violence in Colombia today is even worse than in the days when
druglord Pablo Escobar ran the dreaded Medellin cocaine cartel,
Santos said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The worst is still to come,'' he said. ''Now, we don't know
who is shooting at us, where the bullets come from, why or when.''
</P>
<P>
   Santos urged international press organizations to set up
monitoring groups in Colombia and issue frequent reports on the
press. Speed is crucial, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We cannot afford annual reports,'' he said. ''We need
solidarity, the sooner the better''.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-12-00 1651 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000612.0076 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 17:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Saudis, Yemen Sign Border Agreement  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   JIDDAH, Saudi Arabia (AP) -- Saudi Arabia and Yemen signed an
agreement Monday expected to end decades of border disputes between
the two countries.
</P>
<P>
   The two countries' relations have ''entered a new era,'' Yemeni
President Ali Abdullah Saleh told a news conference after meeting
with Saudi Crown Prince Abdullah. The agreement was signed by the
countries' foreign ministers.
</P>
<P>
   Yemen, which lies on the southwestern tip of the Arabian
peninsula, has long contested Saudi Arabia's claim to three Red Sea
islands and parts of the Empty Quarter, a vast desert region with
potentially lucrative oil deposits.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement draws new borders in the Empty Quarter, Saleh
said. It also provides for the withdrawal of troops to a point
about 12 miles from the borders.
</P>
<P>
   ''Based on brotherhood and neighborliness, we were able to
overcome a number of points of conflict,'' Saleh said, noting that
many in the Arab world doubted the two sides would be able to reach
an accord.
</P>
<P>
   Saudi Defense Minister Prince Sultan bin Abdel-Aziz said the
agreement ''serves the two countries and their peoples.''
</P>
<P>
   No details were released about how the pact handles the Red Sea
islands. The Saudi defense minister was expected to hold a news
conference Wednesday to explain details of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Later Monday, Saleh and Abdullah left separately for the Syrian
capital of Damascus to attend Tuesday's funeral for late President
Hafez Assad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
