<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> House Passes College Security Bill  </HEADLINE>
By JIM ABRAMS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Universities would be required to notify
parents and students of the presence of any students or campus
employees charged or convicted of rape or other violent sex crimes
under a bill that passed the House on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, which was approved by voice vote, takes other
steps to improve campus safety and security, including requiring
schools to make known their policies on investigating and notifying
parents about missing students.
</P>
<P>
   Universities receiving public funds also would have to notify
students and parents about the status of fire alarms and sprinklers
in dorms.
</P>
<P>
   The new security measures were attached to a bill that makes
mostly technical changes to a 1998 law that made it easier for
lower income students to attend institutions of higher learning.
</P>
<P>
   One provision makes clear that lower income students who receive
federal funds for higher education but have to withdraw from school
will never have to return more than 50 percent of the grant.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Howard ''Buck'' McKeon, R-Calif., the sponsor of the
legislation, said he hoped this would allow low-income students to
make another attempt at school.
</P>
<P>
   Under the 1998 law, students earn a certain amount of aid as
they go through the semester. The unearned part is open for
repayment if they withdraw, but a students' repayment obligations
are fulfilled after he completes 60 percent of the term.
</P>
<P>
   The Education Department, in a letter last week to Education
Committee Chairman William Goodling, R-Pa., said it favored
one-time forgiveness for students who withdraw, but voiced concern
that forgiveness for further withdrawals could become a
disincentive for students to complete their programs.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Thomas Petri, R-Wis., also said he was worried about
abuses. ''If there is a theoretical way for people to take
advantage of the government, some people will find it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Mark Souder, R-Ind., said he had also clarified language in
the original law barring the granting of loans to students
convicted of drug offenses. He said students would lose their loans
only if convicted after they had received the loan.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, which now goes to the Senate, also provides for
loan forgiveness for public defenders and prosecutors who earn less
than $30,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The bill number is H.R. 4504.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-12-00 1712 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000612.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 17:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fugitive Paraguayan Arrested  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Smiling and waving to onlookers, a
former Paraguayan army chief wanted in connection with the killing
of his nation's vice president was jailed Monday in Brazil's
capital while he awaits a ruling on his extradition.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Lino Oviedo was flown to Brasilia on Monday just hours
after his arrest in Foz do Iguacu, a tourist resort city on
Brazil's border with Paraguay and Argentina. Guards took him to
federal police headquarters and locked him in a cell reserved for
special prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   ''We only have one cell like that, so he's sharing it with three
other prisoners,'' federal police spokeswoman Viviane da Rosa said.
</P>
<P>
   The next step in the case will be a Brazilian Supreme Court
ruling on whether Oviedo should be extradited to Paraguay.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for Oviedo said they would file a petition Monday for
his release pending a decision on extradition. But Supreme Court
spokesman Gerson Matos said later that no request had been made on
Oviedo's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Oviedo was arrested late Sunday in a penthouse apartment in a
middle-class district of Foz do Iguacu, a city known for its
spectacular waterfalls and slack border controls about 220 miles
east of Asuncion, the capital of Paraguay.
</P>
<P>
   Oviedo was alone in the apartment and did not resist arrest, da
Rosa said. Police found 10 cellular phones and a loaded .38
revolver in the apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Da Rosa said Oviedo showed a false ID card with the name of
Emilio Franco Villareal, a Paraguayan citizen. She said he was
charged with carrying a gun without a license and using false
documents.
</P>
<P>
   With a mustache and long hair over his collar, Oviedo looked
very different from the neatly trimmed figure on news broadcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Brazilian police had been searching for Oviedo since May 26,
when the Supreme Court issued an arrest warrant at the request of
the Paraguayan government.
</P>
<P>
   A former presidential candidate, Oviedo is accused of plotting
the 1999 killing of Vice President Luis Argana. He also was
convicted of leading an unsuccessful coup attempt in 1996 and is
suspected of planning another on May 18 of this year.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1996 attempt, Oviedo was sentenced to 10 years in
prison. He was released after just six months by then-President
Raul Cubas and went into exile in Argentina. Cubas himself was
accused of supporting Argana's killing and was forced to resign and
seek political asylum in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   In Argentina, Oviedo was protected by former President Carlos
Menem, who refused Paraguay's request for extradition. But Menem's
successor, Fernando de la Rua, said he would reconsider that
position. On Dec. 9, a day before de la Rua took office, Oviedo
eluded his Argentine security in the far southern region of Tierra
del Fuego and vanished.
</P>
<P>
   Paraguayan authorities said intelligence agents traced his phone
calls to Foz do Iguacu.
</P>
<P>
   ''He never stopped talking on the phone,'' Paraguayan Defense
Minister Walter Argana said in Asuncion. ''We have 90 hours of
tapes of his conversations with his collaborators.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-12-00 1726 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000612.0080 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 17:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Elderly woman rescued after being 'fused' to her couch  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) - Emergency crews used cutting tools to
rescue a neglected elderly woman who had spent as many as the last
four weeks physically stuck to her couch.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Zurek, 78, was hospitalized and was listed in serious
condition on Monday after she was ''fused to her couch,'' in what
Erie County Medical Center officials have called one of the worst
cases of neglect they have ever seen.
</P>
<P>
   Zurek, rescued Sunday evening, had been stuck to her couch when
fluids from open sores on her back and legs had leaked onto the
sofa and hardened, acting like glue, Buffalo Police Lt. Larry
Baehre said. Buffalo fire and emergency medical officials had to
cut into the couch to release the woman, Baehre said.
</P>
<P>
   Her two sons, who apparently lived with Zurek at the east-side
home, were being questioned by police, who are also considering
asking a state agency on elderly abuse to investigate.
</P>
<P>
   This was the second case of elderly neglect recorded in Buffalo
in less than a week.
</P>
<P>
   Agnes Hail, 76, died in a hospital on Monday afternoon, six days
after she was found in her home covered with maggots and bedsores.
</P>
<P>
   Hail lived with her son, who is reported to be mentally
incompetent. Police noted that two of her daughters lived nearby.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, authorities are investigating whether charges of
criminally negligent homicide should be laid against those who were
supposed to take care of Hail.
</P>
<P>
   Erie County District Attorney is sorting through the information
to see whether criminal charges are warranted.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you're living with mom and she can't take care of herself,
you have to do it,'' Clark said. ''And if you don't do it, maybe
your failure is a crime.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
