<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Death penalty hearing set to begin on boy witness case  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRIDGEPORT, Conn. (AP) - The same jury that convicted Russell
Peeler Jr. in the murders of an 8-year-old witness and the boy's
mother is set to begin a hearing to determine whether Peeler will
spend the rest of his life in prison or die by lethal injection.
</P>
<P>
   Although the murders of Leroy ''B.J.'' Brown Jr. and his mother,
Karen Clarke, sparked widespread public outrage, there are
drastically differing opinions on whether Peeler should get the
death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   A jury of five women and seven men will ultimately decide.
</P>
<P>
   Peeler was convicted last week of arranging the murders of B.J.
and his mother to prevent the little boy from testifying against
him in an earlier murder case.
</P>
<P>
   Peeler was convicted on two counts of capital felony: killing a
child under the age of 16 and killing two people at the same time.
Under the law, must be sentenced to either life in prison without
the possibility of release or execution.
</P>
<P>
   The death penalty phase of Peeler's trial is scheduled to begin
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Peeler's lawyers will present evidence of mitigating factors,
while prosecutors will present evidence of aggravating factors. The
jury will then be asked to weigh aggravating factors against
mitigating factors in determining whether Peeler should receive the
death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors plan to present evidence of four different
aggravating factors, including the argument that the murders were
committed ''in an especially heinous, cruel and depraved manner.''
The state also plans to argue that Peeler paid co-conspirator
Josephine Lee with crack cocaine to assist in the crime.
Prosecutors say Peeler also paid Gary Garner, the suspected driver
of the getaway car.
</P>
<P>
   Peeler's attorneys would not say what mitigating factors they
plan to argue. But under the state's death penalty law, they are
allowed to argue factors spelled out in the statute and other, more
general factors such as a troubled childhood.
</P>
<P>
   Before the state's death penalty law was amended in 1995, if a
jury found just one mitigating factor - either those specified by
the statute or more general factors - the death penalty could not
be imposed.
</P>
<P>
   The current law allows juries to weigh mitigating and
aggravating factors, but still prohibits the death penalty if the
jury finds one of the four mitigating factors spelled out in the
statute. Those factors are: if the defendant was under 18; if his
mental capacity was significantly impaired; if he was criminally
liable for the offense but his participation was relatively minor;
or he could not reasonably have foreseen that his conduct would
create a grave risk of causing death.
</P>
<P>
   In Peeler's case, his lawyers may argue that his participation
was relatively minor because his brother, Adrian, is accused of
being the actual triggerman. Adrian Peeler, who also faces capital
felony charges, will be tried later.
</P>
<P>
   It's been 40 years since the death penalty has been used in
Connecticut. Joseph ''Mad Dog'' Taborsky was executed on May 17,
1960, after a murder and robbery spree. Six people are now on death
row.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the Peeler case, where there was a public outcry over
the killing of a little boy, there is a reluctance among some to
call for the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   State Rep. Chris Caruso, D-Bridgeport, was one of the most vocal
critics of the state's judicial system for failing to protect B.J.
from Peeler, a notorious drug dealer who B.J. had promised to
testify against in the killing of his mother's boyfriend, Rudolph
Snead Jr. Yet, Caruso says he has mixed feelings about giving
Peeler the death penalty.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think you could ever forgive in a situation like this,
but maybe the just punishment is to have him serve the rest of his
life in jail and have him reflect on how he threw away his life and
also how he ended the life of such a promising young man and his
mother,'' Caruso said. ''That may be torture in itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Waterbury State's Attorney John Connelly, who has prosecuted
four of the six men now on death row, wouldn't comment on the
Peeler case specifically, but said sometimes the death penalty is
the only just punishment.
</P>
<P>
   ''In some cases the crimes are so vicious and so heinous that
the person who has committed the crime has demonstrated through his
conduct that he no longer belongs in society and, in fact, he is a
danger even if he is incarcerated,'' Connelly said.
</P>
<P>
   But Ronald Gold, a senior attorney in the Chief Public
Defender's Office, said the state should not be in the business of
retribution. He also would not comment on the Peeler case.
</P>
<P>
   ''In a case where a guy's been convicted of a capital offense, I
think that the only appropriate sentence is prison without the
possibility of release. That certainly protects society and it is a
significant form of justice and a punishment,'' Gold said.
</P>
<P>
   Clarke's brother, Oswald, said he wants Peeler prosecuted ''to
the full extent of the law, whatever that is.'' He said he would
leave it up to the jury to decide whether Peeler lives or dies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-12-00 1729 </TRAILER>
