<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Newark lags behind nation in Census response rates  </HEADLINE>
By AMY WESTFELDT
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - Language barriers, a low response in the
black community and a high turnover rate among Census enumerators
have caused Newark to lag far behind the nation in Census response
rates, officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Census Bureau Director Kenneth Prewitt appeared in the state's
largest city Monday to rally Census workers to get a complete
count. Newark is a stop on a national tour of some of the country's
lowest performing cities, including Milwaukee, Baltimore and
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every Census office in the country hits what we call the
wall,'' Prewitt said Monday. ''In a city like Newark, you hit that
wall a little sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 82 percent of all households have turned in Census
forms in Newark, compared to a national average of over 98 percent.
Overall, New Jersey has a 96.2 percent response rate.
</P>
<P>
   Census workers are still seeking responses from 23,000
households that didn't mail back forms and have been unreachable
door to door, said Lester A. Farthing, the Census Bureau's regional
director for New York City and northern New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Prewitt and other officials said many Newark residents are
immigrants who have trouble speaking English and may be afraid of
the government. But Newark has fared worse than Jersey City, which
also has a diverse ethnic population but has a response rate of
nearly 92 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''Newark has a higher percentage of people in its general
population who don't understand the purposes of a Census and who
aren't fully committed to it,'' Prewitt said.
</P>
<P>
   Farthing said the city's black community, which makes up at
least half of Newark's population, has had an extremely low
response rate. He also blamed problems on high turnover rates with
Census enumerators.
</P>
<P>
   ''This job isn't for everybody,'' Farthing said. When Census
workers knock on doors ''and they get yelled at the first time,
that can turn them off right away.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the turnover rate among approximately 400 enumerators is
over 20 percent, despite the $18.50 an hour Census enumerators
make. The salary is the highest in the nation for Census
enumerators, matching New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Officials pointed out that while Newark lags behind the nation
and the rest of the state, it is ahead of where it was 10 years
ago. At this time in 1990, the city had only reached 61 percent of
its population, Prewitt said. The Census Bureau and state
governments launched massive advertising campaigns this year to
ensure a more complete count.
</P>
<P>
   An incomplete Census count can result in losses of hundreds of
millions of dollars in state and federal aid and in political
representation.
</P>
<P>
   The city faces a July 7 national deadline to turn in a complete
count, but Prewitt said the enumerators would stay in Newark until
the job is done.
</P>
<P>
   The city plans to open all its firehouses 24 hours a day next
week to encourage people who haven't turned in Census forms to show
up, said Deputy Mayor Luigi Campana, who is coordinating the city's
Census outreach efforts.
</P>
<P>
   And Farthing said the city is trying to better match its
counters with its population. For example, a female senior citizen
is less likely to open her door to a younger person, he said. And
he also said he's found the right people to try to solicit forms
from unresponsive young bachelors.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have some beautiful women in Newark, and if that's what it
takes to get that door to open, that's what we'll do,'' Farthing
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-12-00 1733 </TRAILER>
