<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Violence against tourists, others, mars summer weekend  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - Six people were killed and 59 others were
stabbed or shot around the city over the weekend. In Central Park,
a group of young men stripped and groped four women, including
tourists from France and England; a bias attack occurred in Coney
Island.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the spate of violence over the hot, humid weekend, the
mayor and police commissioner were quick to point out on Monday
that crime is still down from last year, and considerably lower
than a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know if I'm concerned with public perception,'' Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani said in response to a reporter's question. ''I'm
concerned with reality.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the more brazen attacks occurred Sunday in crowded
Central Park. Shortly after 6 p.m., about 15 men, some carrying
large water pistols, squirted six women with water, then tore off
the clothes off of four of them and groped them. All the attacks
took place in heavily traveled areas - along Central Park South,
near the zoo and the Plaza Hotel. Five of the women were robbed of
money and jewelry.
</P>
<P>
   The men first attacked two Long Island teens, ages 16 and 18.
Then they targeted a couple visiting from France, restraining the
29-year-old man while they stripped and fondled his 28-year-old
wife. About 30 minutes later, three women, ages 18 and 19, visiting
from England, were attacked by the group.
</P>
<P>
   ''She was naked, completely naked. We were mortified,'' said
native New Yorker Rita Berlin, who saw police aiding one of the
victims.
</P>
<P>
   David Rowe, 24, of Hempstead, on Long Island, and Tremayne Bane,
23, of Brooklyn, were arrested on robbery and sexual abuse charges
after the English victims pointed them out to police. Other
suspects were being sought. Police urged any other victims and
anyone who was using a videocamera in the area to come forward.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir said crime in the 840-acre
Central Park is down this year, but added, ''If I put 10,000 cops
in Central Park, we couldn't cover every single area.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the incident, the park was again crowded on Monday.
''All the tourist books say the city is so much safer these days,
how Times Square has been cleaned up, things like that,'' said
tourist Valerie Izzard, 30, of London. ''That incident makes you
wonder. But I believe it was isolated, and I would not let it deter
me from seeing the park.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Coney Island incident, eight Hasidic men walking along
the boardwalk around 4:30 a.m. on Sunday were beaten, and four of
them stabbed by men who yelled anti-Semitic remarks. There were no
immediate arrests; police declared it a bias crime; the attackers
were described as Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   In other acts of violence, six people were injured in Brooklyn
by a man brandishing an Uzi, and two women were hurt when three men
armed with a blow-dart gun drove by and shot at them, also in
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   And three people were stabbed on Manhattan's Upper East Side on
Sunday. There were no immediate arrests; the victims, who police
said had apparently just attended the Puerto Rican Day parade, were
expected to make full recoveries.
</P>
<P>
   Six people were killed Saturday and Sunday, including one man
involved in a Harlem shootout and another, in the Bronx, stabbed in
a fight over money. The others were described as disputes in which
the victim and assailant knew each other.
</P>
<P>
   According to the latest police statistics, through June 4,
murders have increased almost 6 percent from 281 during the same
period last year, to 297 this year. Shootings have risen nearly 7
percent from 791 last year to 846.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the last month and a half, homicide is actually down; and
over the year, crime is down between 7 and 8 percent,'' said
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's unrealistic to assume,'' the mayor added, ''that police
officers can be everywhere at every time.''
</P>
<P>
   -
</P>
<P>
   Rowe address: 66D Martin Luther Dr., Hempstead.
</P>
<P>
   Bane address: 91 E. 21st St., Brooklyn.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
