<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scientists Oppose Missile Shield  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- American scientists opposed to a limited
national missile defense program asserted Monday that the
Pentagon's plan for such a shield won't work and should be put on
hold.
</P>
<P>
   ''It may never be ready. This is basically a flawed process,''
said Kurt Gottfried, a physics professor at Cornell University in
Ithaca, N.Y., and chairman of the Union of Concerned Scientists.
</P>
<P>
   About 35 scientists and engineers told a Capitol news conference
the proposed system to shoot down ballistic missiles fired at the
United States from terrorist countries is scientifically unsound,
no matter how politically popular.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Danchick, a retired missile expert who worked for defense
contractor TRW, cited ''a fatal rush to deployment with a system
that can't work.''
</P>
<P>
   Under heavy congressional pressure, President Clinton is to
decide this fall whether to deploy such a system. His decision will
come after another interception test in early July and the Pentagon
makes its recommendation in late summer.
</P>
<P>
   The scientists said the $60 billion system could easily be
defeated by countermeasures, such as hiding warheads among a flock
of decoy balloons, that any nation capable of producing a ballistic
missile could fabricate.
</P>
<P>
   Voicing an opposing view, Rep. Curt Weldon, R-Pa., a leading
congressional missile-defense advocate, said in a statement, ''For
the longest time, these Luddites insisted that national missile
defense would never work.''
</P>
<P>
   But Weldon, who was traveling in Russia with Defense Secretary
William Cohen, said, ''The Department of Defense is moving forward
with an effective national missile defense that will be able to
discern between countermeasures.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics have claimed the Pentagon rigged recent tests of an
anti-missile interceptor rocket by using simple decoys.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon acknowledged last week that it used simpler decoys
in recent flight tests but said stepping down the decoy quality was
according to plan and did not amount to dishonest manipulation to
hide a fatal flaw, as had been alleged.
</P>
<P>
   An October test hit the mock warhead, but the interceptor missed
its target in the most recent test, in January. The next test is
scheduled for early July, and more than a dozen others are planned.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was unsuccessful in his recent meeting in Moscow to win
Russian President Vladimir Putin's agreement to modify the 1972
Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty to permit such a missile-defense
system.
</P>
<P>
   Some missile-defense advocates want the United States to
withdraw from the treaty and build the missile system anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The plan envisioned by the administration would involve a
limited system designed to counter a small number of missiles, such
as might be launched by North Korea, Iran or Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush has suggested
he would like a more elaborate system.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the net: Defense Department site: http://www.defenselink.mil
</P>
<P>
   Union of Concerned Scientists: http://www.ucsusa.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-12-00 1740 </TRAILER>
