<DOCNO> APW20000612.0095 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki slams Gore's ''progress and prosperity tour''  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - On the eve of Al Gore's ''progress and
prosperity'' presidential campaign tour, Republican Gov. George
Pataki on Monday accused the vice president of unfairly trying to
claim credit for the nation's economic boom.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the height of hypocrisy for the man who claims to have
invented the Internet to now claim he's invented prosperity,'' said
Pataki, who leads Texas Gov. George W. Bush's New York presidential
campaign effort.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said any credit for the economic boom due politicians
should go to governors, both Republicans and Democrats, and to
Republican congressional forces, but not to President Clinton or
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ''He believes in Washington, he believes in government and that
is precisely the philosophy that in the 70s under President Carter
led us to our period of malaise,'' the New York governor added.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki called the Gore tour ''an insult to the intelligence of
the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   A Gore campaign spokesman said Pataki was backing the wrong
horse if he was concerned about the nation's economic prosperity in
the future.
</P>
<P>
   ''The governor ignores the fact that the last time a Bush was in
the White House, we were suffering a painful recession,'' said Doug
Hattaway. ''Al Gore was part of the team that helped balance the
budget and pay down the national debt which helped create the
climate for our current prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking to energize his presidential campaign, Democrat Gore
planned to begin his tour with a Tuesday afternoon speech in New
York City. While New York is considered a safe state for the vice
president, aides felt he could grab major national media attention
by starting his tour there.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Gore was to speak in Pennsylvania about health
care and, on Thursday, he was to be in Ohio to talk about tax cuts.
Both Pennsylvania and Ohio are considered swing states that could
help determine the election outcome.
</P>
<P>
   All three states have something in common - Republican
governors. And all three - Pataki, Tom Ridge in Pennsylvania and
Bob Taft in Ohio - are Bush backers.
</P>
<P>
   ''The fact that he's going to three states where Republican
governors have truly turned around the economic climate with tax
cuts and control over spending and other pro-business fiscal
policies, I think points out the differences between what a Gore
administration would do and what a Bush administration would do,''
Pataki said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the Clinton administration deserved any credit for
the nation's economic prosperity, Pataki said that Federal Reserve
Chairman ''Alan Greenspan deserves some of the credit because his
policies have been positive ... but I certainly think the
foundation for this was laid by the Reagan tax cuts and has been
carried forward at the state level by governors.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Ultimately, the credit goes to the American people and the
American entrepreneurs,'' the New York governor added.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said some Clinton administration policies have hindered
economic growth in the state and that Gore ''has never seen a tax
cut he doesn't deem risky.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has criticized Bush's proposed tax-cut plan as ''risky,''
but Pataki said Monday that he is backing the Bush plan completely
and thinks it would be good for New York.
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Hattaway said, ''Governor Pataki is backing a
candidate who has little experience with managing national economic
issues and is pushing a tax cut that would keep us from paying down
the (national) debt.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said he had not been contacted by the Bush campaign about
criticizing Gore's tour and had come up with the idea on his own.
Gore heads for Scranton, Pa., on Tuesday night. Ridge plans to
campaign in the Scranton area on Tuesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-12-00 1741 </TRAILER>
