<DOCNO> APW20000612.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 50,000 Displaced Congolese Return  </HEADLINE>
By HRVOJE HRANJSKI
<TEXT>
<P>
   KISANGANI, Congo (AP) -- Tens of thousands of war-weary Congolese
poured into Kisangani on Monday, returning to their families and
shattered homes at the end of a seven-day bombardment by Rwandan
and Ugandan forces.
</P>
<P>
   A woman cried ''Papa,'' hugging her father after worrying about
him for a week. Mothers with crying babies on their backs crossed a
key bridge over the Tshopo River under the scorching sun where
unarmed U.N. military observers watched the steady flow of human
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Blue U.N. flags flew at both ends of the bridge that now
separates Rwandan and Ugandan forces after the Rwandans pushed the
Ugandans north across the river on Sunday. Ugandan forces tried for
a week to move into Kisangani, Congo's third-largest city between
the Tshopo and Congo Rivers.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Col. Danilo Paiva, head of the 30-strong observer team, said
about 50,000 people were on the move, crossing back into the city
after fleeing into Ugandan-controlled northern Congo when the
fighting erupted between the two armies June 5.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear why the fighting began after the two sides had
agreed to a prearranged withdrawal from the city.
</P>
<P>
   At least 150 Congolese civilians were killed in the week of
shelling and shooting, and 1,000 others were injured. The Rwandan
and Ugandan armies did not disclose their casualties.
</P>
<P>
   ''When the Ugandans set up weapons in front of my house and
started shooting, I fled across the bridge,'' said Joseph Ilumbe,
61. ''I don't know what has happened to my house or my family.''
</P>
<P>
   Rwandan military spokesman Maj. Emmanuel Ndahiro said in the
Rwandan capital, Kigali, that the Rwandans would meet this week
with Senegalese Gen. Muntaga Diallo, head of the U.N. military
observer mission in Congo to discuss their withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   Diallo heads the 100-strong observer mission created under a
peace accord signed last summer to bring an end to the civil war in
Congo. The U.N. is to deploy 5,537 more troops to protect the
monitors as they verify the cease-fire throughout Africa's
third-largest nation.
</P>
<P>
   Initially allies backing the same group that rebelled against
Congolese President Laurent Kabila in August 1998, Rwanda and
Uganda fell out as the rebel movement split in two over how to
conduct the war. Zimbabwe, Angola and Namibia are backing Kabila.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, The U.N. Security Council on Monday condemned the
fighting between Rwandan and Ugandan troops in Kisangani and said
it expects the two sides to abide by pledges to fully withdraw from
the city.
</P>
<P>
   The council also said it was concerned about the statement from
the Congolese government that it no longer supported an
African-appointed facilitator, former Botswana president Ketumile
Masire.
</P>
<P>
   Congo's justice minister, Mwenze Kongolo, made the statement
late Sunday after visiting the Angolan capital Luanda, where he
briefed Congo's military ally in the latest developments in the
fighting. Kongolo also accused the United Nations of siding with
the rebels -- a charge U.N. officials deny.
</P>
<P>
   The council said it was concerned about ''violent
demonstrations'' over the weekend at U.N. headquarters in the
Congolese capital, Kinshasa.
</P>
<P>
   Life slowly returned to normal Monday in Kisangani with the
familiar din of cars, bicycles and shouting Congolese traders.
Kisangani's normally vibrant central market reopened, although most
of the wooden stalls stood empty. Instead of the usual smoked
monkey and fish, traders offered soap and cigarettes from
pre-fighting stocks.
</P>
<P>
   But the uncollected bodies of Ugandan soldiers still lay in the
city's streets, covered by white cloths, awaiting Red Cross
volunteers to collect them. Rwandan army officials said they had
counted at least 140 bodies.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Cross was trying to arrange for their transfer to the
Ugandan side.
</P>
<P>
   Unexploded mortar shells lay in the streets as did spent shells
and empty cartridges. On Sunday, three children died and one was
injured while playing with unexploded hand grenades, the Red Cross
said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. World Food Program flew in 1.5 tons of maize meal,
beans and high-protein biscuits on Monday, and another 35 tons of
food were expected on Tuesday, regional WFP spokeswoman Brenda
Barton said in Nairobi, Kenya.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
