<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Photos of missing persons to be posted on state websites  </HEADLINE>
By HADLEY PAWLAK
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - Police say the first 48 to 72 hours in a
missing person's case are critical. After that, hopes of recovering
the individual become dim.
</P>
<P>
   But a new initiative by the state - the ''Missing Person Alert''
program - aims to assist the search by spreading instantaneous
photos and information about a missing person over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's in the first few hours when you can follow the movement
of the missing person,'' Lt. Jamie Mills of the New York State
Police said Monday. ''As times goes by, the trail goes cold.''
</P>
<P>
   When an investigation finds a disappearance may have involved
foul play or some criminal element, the missing person's picture
and descriptive data would be posted as an ''alert'' at the top of
state websites.
</P>
<P>
   Clicking on the alert would lead to a site with more information
and a ''Missing Person'' poster that can be downloaded and printed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Before, we had to fax these out, but now they can be printed
right at the (Thruway) toll plazas and posted very, very quickly,''
Mills said.
</P>
<P>
   Initially the alerts will be posted on the websites of the State
Police, Metropolitan Transportation Authority, Thruway Authority
and the Department of Transportation. Combined, those sites have
43,000 visitors a day, according to Lt. Gov. Mary Donohue.
</P>
<P>
   ''The majority of those (website visitors) are the motoring
public who are traveling across geographic lines and have a chance
of seeing and maybe recognizing the person and giving us a
contact,'' said James McMahon, superintendent of the New York State
Police.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the alert will be posted on over 90 state-affiliated
websites, Donohue said.
</P>
<P>
   New York state has long used the traveling public to aid in
searches for missing people. Thruway toll plazas feature pictures
of missing people and in the mid-1980's, pictures of missing
children were printed on the back of toll tickets.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got to be able to track movement,'' Mills said. ''Soon
after an abduction it's likely that people will travel out of the
area on the Thruway.''
</P>
<P>
   Alerts will stay posted on the state websites for one week and
will be reposted every time additional information or leads are
produced.
</P>
<P>
   Close to 36,000 people are reported missing in New York state
each year. Using the Internet to help find them came at the
recommendation of Doug and Mary Lyall, whose 19-year-old daughter
Suzanne has been missing for more than two years.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Lyall was a computer science major at the University at
Albany at the time of her disappearance. The Lyalls created a
website soon after she disappeared with photos of Suzanne, letters
to her abductor, links to information about other missing women and
ways to contact them with information on their daughter's
whereabouts.
</P>
<P>
   ''If an alert helps even one family find a loved one, it will be
a great success,'' said Doug Lyall.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Help Us Find Suzanne: http://www.global2000.net/suzy/
</P>
<P>
   New York State Troopers: http://www.troopers.state.ny.us
</P>
<P>
   New York State Thruway Authority: http://www.thruway.state.ny.us
</P>
<P>
   New York State Dept. of Transportation:
http://www.dot.state.ny.us
</P>
<P>
   Metropolitan Transit Authority: http://www.mta.nyc.ny.us
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
