<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 17:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lazio says he backs 'hate crimes' legislation  </HEADLINE>
By JOEL STASHENKO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - U.S. Rep. Rick Lazio said Monday he supports
a ''hate crimes'' law to provide for higher penalties for offenses
committed on the basis of a victim's race, gender, religion or
sexual orientation.
</P>
<P>
   ''People ought not to be subject to violence because of their
background,'' Lazio said, adding that such crimes have ''a
particularly corrosive impact on society.''
</P>
<P>
   Following a private meeting with Republicans who control the
state Senate, the U.S. Senate opponent of Hillary Rodham Clinton
said he backs the measure supported by 24 of the 36 GOP state
senators last week. The legislation was proposed by Republican Gov.
George Pataki and passed the Senate, 48-12.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Clinton supporters questioned Lazio's support for
hate crimes legislation after discovering he had abstained during a
vote on the subject in 1990 while in the Suffolk County
Legislature. The county measure had called on the state Senate to
pass a hate crimes bill.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has been closely identified with a hate crimes bill in
Albany, appearing earlier this spring at the Capitol to publicly
lobby for the Senate to pass the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio met Monday for the first time formally with Senate
Republicans since he became the GOP's candidate to oppose Clinton
on May 30. After the closed-door session, Majority Leader Joseph
Bruno declared, ''I can't think of anything that we are not really
in sync on and this conference is unanimously supporting him in
every way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate probably will not make Lazio happy on one issue the
congressman has pushed for in Washington, however.
</P>
<P>
   A measure which would allow some disabled people in New York to
continue receiving Medicaid benefits while holding private jobs is
supported by Senate Republicans, but is not likely to pass before
the Senate concludes its regular 2000 session, Bruno said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Are we open, are we talking?'' Bruno asked. ''The answer is
yes. Do I expect we are going to get to it these next couple of
days? The answer is no.''
</P>
<P>
   Lazio said he would continue lobbying for the so-called Medicaid
''buy-in'' in Albany, but conceded ''there are some fiscal issues
that the state has, they are real issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Privately, legislators say Pataki is opposing the buy-in, which
could cost the state at least $14 million a year, unless lawmakers
can show where that money will come from.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio reiterated his opposition to federal gun licensing and
said bullet ''fingerprinting'' and other technological advances
should be employed to keep guns out of the hands of criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio also pressed the flesh Monday with employees and visitors
to the sprawling Empire State Plaza office complex in Albany. His
aides took him on a rather confused tour of the first floor of the
Capitol, with a troop of reporters trailing behind. He walked down
a hallway and then doubled back before finding where a waiting car
was parked to drive him to the exclusive Fort Orange Club nearby
for a meeting with supporters.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Lazio ran into Pataki in the Empire State Plaza.
The congressman's brief chat with the governor was the only contact
the two Republican allies had on Monday, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   ''My partner,'' Lazio declared as Pataki hurried away to attend
an event in the office complex.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
