<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Judge hands city another First Amendment loss  </HEADLINE>
By LARRY NEUMEISTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - The latest in a string of First Amendment losses
for the administration of Mayor Rudolph Giuliani came Monday when a
federal judge said rent increase protesters can lie or sleep on a
city sidewalk.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. District Judge Kimba Wood said ''core First Amendment
rights to political protest are at stake'' in the plans by the
Metropolitan Council Inc., a tenants' advocacy organization, to
stage the protest.
</P>
<P>
   The group contends that rent increases proposed by the city's
Rent Guidelines Board would increase homelessness in the city,
clogging more sidewalks with people sleeping on flattened cardboard
boxes.
</P>
<P>
   The group planned to stage a vigil at a park beginning Tuesday
near Giuliani's residence, Gracie Mansion. The plan included having
protesters lying on the ground in the park from 8 p.m. until 1
a.m., when up to 25 protesters were going to move to a stretch of
sidewalk opposite Gracie Mansion, where they would remain until 8
a.m.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Metropolitan Council sought a court declaration
that the city could not interfere with its protest. The New York
Civil Liberties Union said after Wood issued her ruling that the
protest would occur as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   The city had opposed the request, saying a total ban on sleeping
on city sidewalks protects people who do not understand the dangers
of sleeping in public places, and keeps sidewalks clear of
obstructions.
</P>
<P>
   Wood listened to arguments by both sides in the dispute Friday
and issued a written ruling Monday, finding that the First
Amendment ''does not allow the city to prevent an orderly political
protest from using public sleeping as a means of symbolic
expression.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge rejected the city's reasoning that allowing the
protest means it cannot ever regulate disorderly public sleeping.
</P>
<P>
   Wood said there were ''obvious and dramatic differences''
between what the protesters had planned and the intentions of
others who might sleep on sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Hess, the city's top lawyer, said Wood was wrong but
added he doubted the city would appeal because the ruling was
limited to the protesters who sought the court's protection.
</P>
<P>
   Hess, though, said the city would consider arresting the
protesters at the conclusion of the demonstration if any laws were
violated.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Judge Guido Calabresi on the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals criticized the city, saying, ''We would be ostriches if we
failed to take judicial notice of the heavy stream of First
Amendment litigation generated by New York City in recent years.''
</P>
<P>
   Calabresi noted 18 prominent cases in which the appeals court or
a lower federal court had found one of the city's actions or
policies unconstitutional on First Amendment grounds.
</P>
<P>
   The judge wrote that ''in the current and rather remarkable
state of affairs in New York City,'' there was a danger that the
courts might become an agency that performs crucial local
government functions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
