<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State loses appeal on parole of man who killed two officers  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - A man convicted of killing two police
officers could be in a halfway house by June 19 and on his way to
parole after more than three decades in state prison.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General John J. Farmer Jr. lost an appeal Monday to
block Thomas Trantino's transfer while the state works to overturn
a ruling issued last week that said the convicted killer should be
paroled.
</P>
<P>
   The state appeals court delayed Trantino's move for only seven
days. Farmer's office had sought an indefinite postponement while
appealing the case to the state Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   Late Monday afternoon, a spokesman for Farmer said attorneys
were preparing an emergency appeal to the state Supreme Court. That
appeal was expected to be filed Tuesday morning, said spokesman
Chuck Davis.
</P>
<P>
   The attorney general will ask the Supreme Court to review the
order to parole Trantino, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer will also ask the justices to keep Trantino in a state
prison while they consider the appeal, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Trantino, who was convicted of killing two Lodi police officers
in 1963, has been denied parole at least nine times during his 37
years behind bars.
</P>
<P>
   The lower court last week said Trantino should be immediately
transferred to a halfway house. In that order, the court said state
Department of Corrections officials had 30 days to ready Trantino
for parole.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the Supreme Court does not act, by the 19th he could be in
the halfway house and then on his way out,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   The appellate ruling focuses solely on parole issues, said
Trantino's lawyer Roger Lowenstein. The state disagrees only with
the final outcome, not the legal foundation for the ruling, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   That makes it unlikely the Supreme Court will hear the case,
according to Lowenstein.
</P>
<P>
   ''They don't need to take this case. There are no issues here
that are of any merit,'' Lowenstein said.
</P>
<P>
   A three-judge panel said in a 66-page opinion Friday that
Trantino's latest rejection by the state parole board was ''not
supported by any credible evidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Christie Whitman immediately ordered Farmer to appeal.
Farmer's deputies were able to convince an appeals court judge to
grant the emergency stay Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   But the state lost the second round Monday when the same
appellate panel issued its ruling, Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was no reason given. Essentially they denied us,'' Davis
said.
</P>
<P>
   Trantino had been sentenced to die for killing the two officers
in a bar in August 1963. But when New Jersey's death penalty was
overturned in 1972, Trantino's sentence was changed to life in
prison. Sentencing guidelines in effect at the time made Trantino
eligible for parole in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   After an earlier appeal, Trantino earned another chance at
release and a hearing before the parole board.
</P>
<P>
   At a June 1999 session, the board rejected Trantino's plea for
parole. Board members relied on a number of points, including
claims by prison mental health examiners that he would likely
commit another crime.
</P>
<P>
   But Trantino argued on appeal that parole board members ignored
several key points on his behalf. Trantino cited a prison record
that showed no infractions since 1970 and a private doctor and
other tests that said he appeared to be a good candidate for
parole.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
