<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Montenegro Leadership Claims Victory  </HEADLINE>
By KATARINA KRATOVAC
<TEXT>
<P>
   PODGORICA, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Municipal elections in Montenegro,
Serbia's smaller partner in the Yugoslav federation, left the
country divided Monday between backers of the pro-Western
government and supporters of Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   President Milo Djukanovic's side won 28 of the 54 municipal
posts in Podgorica, the capital, according to results released
Monday by Montenegro's election commission.
</P>
<P>
   Djukanovic's forces, which favor looser ties with Yugoslavia --
if not outright independence -- can now govern the city. Previously,
they had 27 seats.
</P>
<P>
   The results failed, however, to give Djukanovic the ringing
endorsement he sought.
</P>
<P>
   Djukanovic's opponents, under Yugoslav Prime Minister Momir
Bulatovic, claimed an ''absolute victory'' in the coastal resort of
Herceg Novi, the other key city involved in Sunday's elections.
</P>
<P>
   Bulatovic's side wants this tiny mountainous republic to remain
firmly in the federal embrace. Its victory in Herceg Novi is likely
to dissuade Djukanovic from taking a hasty step to full
independence anytime soon and risk an armed conflict with
Milosevic, the Yugoslav president.
</P>
<P>
   Bulatovic's camp said it had won 19 out of the 35 seats there.
The election commission reported Monday it had ''received no
results'' on Herceg Novi balloting and referred journalists instead
to claims published in the newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   Downplaying the loss of Herceg Novi, Djukanovic urged his
followers not to be disheartened and focus instead on the victory
in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   ''This proves Montenegro is stepping forward on the road of
democracy and no one can stop us anymore,'' Djukanovic told
supporters early Monday. ''Milosevic's policies are on their
deathbed.''
</P>
<P>
   Voting would be repeated at one polling station in Podgorica
where minor irregularities were reported but had no bearing on
final results, the election commission also said. After a 72-hour
complaint period, the results are expected to be declared official
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   International monitors from the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe had dispatched 80 observers to the balloting.
Julian Peel Yates, the head of the OSCE in Europe's Montenegro
office, said the election was conducted in line with the group's
requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ''The election campaign was vigorously contested mainly on
national issues against a complex, tense and uncertain political
background,'' he said. ''Nevertheless, fundamental freedoms were
respected and it's noteworthy that campaigning was conducted
peacefully throughout.''
</P>
<P>
   The election commission said the turnout in Podgorica was 78.8
percent,and newspapers reported turnout in Herceg Novi around 70
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Several explanations could account for the victory of the
pro-Milosevic bloc in Herceg Novi.
</P>
<P>
   The town includes a large group of Serb refugees from wars in
the former Yugoslavia who had since acquired Montenegrin
citizenship and eligibility to vote. The refugees are generally
believed more supportive of Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   However, Herceg Novi's new mayor, Djuro Cetkovic, said his side
won because they had the ''support of the people ... support in the
villages.''
</P>
<P>
   ''These are people who have lived for centuries here and cannot
imagine a future without Serbia and Yugoslavia,'' Cetkovic told the
Pobjeda daily.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-12-00 1801 </TRAILER>
