<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 18:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PBS Will Rerun Popular Shows  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- PBS will test a revamped prime-time schedule in
seven markets this fall, moving a long-running drama series to
Monday nights and running repeats of two of its most popular shows.
</P>
<P>
   If the pilot project goes well, the PBS schedule for the entire
country could be changed as early as April.
</P>
<P>
   PBS, which seldom fiddles with its schedule, will have the
''Exxonmobil Masterpiece Theatre'' and ''American Experience'' swap
their Sunday and Monday time slots. The idea is the drama
presentation would do better on Mondays with less network
competition, spokesman Tom Epstein said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Nature,'' which airs on Sunday nights, will switch to Fridays,
and ''Mystery!'' moves from Thursdays to Tuesdays.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, PBS will feature same-week repeats.
''Antiques Roadshow,'' which premieres new episodes on Sunday
night, will rerun them on Wednesdays. ''Nova,'' which has new
episodes Tuesdays, will air reruns on Thursdays.
</P>
<P>
   It's a tactic used frequently by cable networks but not as often
by broadcasters. Epstein said it will mean fewer spots on the
schedule for first-run programming, but is likely to increase the
audience for PBS' popular shows.
</P>
<P>
   The new schedule will be tested at PBS stations in Orlando,
Fla., Pittsburgh, Philadelphia, Atlanta, Salt Lake City, Cleveland
and San Diego.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-12-00 1805 </TRAILER>
