<DOCNO> APW20000612.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 18:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pataki nominates former Freedom Party head to wagering board  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The former chairwoman of the defunct Freedom
Party was nominated Monday by Gov. George Pataki as a member of the
state Racing and Wagering Board.
</P>
<P>
   If confirmed by the state Senate, Cheryl Buley would be the
first woman to serve on the three-member board, which oversees all
the state's legalized gambling activities, including thoroughbred
and harness horse racing and off-track betting, except for the
state Lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki said Buley, who has worked for Senate Majority Leader
Joseph Bruno, ''gained a working knowledge of the horse racing
industry working for Senator Bruno that will serve the board
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Buley worked for Bruno in 1985-86 before moving to public
relations firms in Boston and Albany. In 1994, she became
chairwoman of the Freedom Party, a creation of the state Republican
Party to add another party line backing Pataki during his first run
for governor. The Freedom Party was disbanded after Pataki won the
election.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki tapped Buley for the post after a printing executive
withdrew his name from consideration last week. Salvatore ''Skip''
DeBiase, founder and CEO of Phoenix Graphics Inc. in Rochester,
said that his family and business commitments would not give him
enough time to serve as a board member.
</P>
<P>
   Buley's husband, Jeffrey Buley, is a lawyer for the state
Republican Chairman William Powers and has a lobbying partnership
with Albert Pirro. Pirro, a lobbyist and developer who is married
to Westchester County District Attorney Jeanine Pirro, is being
tried in federal court in White Plains for tax evasion.
</P>
<P>
   State law prohibits all three board members from being members
of the same political party. The board's other two members,
Chairman Michael Hoblock and Joseph Neglia, are both Republicans.
Buley, not enrolled in a political party, filed forms Monday to
retain that independent status and thus qualify for the
$101,600-a-year job.
</P>
<P>
   She had earlier filed forms to become an enrolled Republican
after this November's elections.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki's nomination drew criticism from Democrats, who
questioned Buley's political affiliation and her job experience.
They want the governor to reappoint Bennett Liebman, a Democrat who
has served two six-year terms on the board. Liebman's term expired
in February.
</P>
<P>
   ''Why are we replacing somebody who is eminently qualified for
the job, who has demonstrated a nonpartisan approach to the board,
with somebody who appears to have no qualification for the job,''
said Bill Reynolds, a spokesman for Senate Minority Leader Martin
Connor, D-Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ''It all seems very murky, Reynolds added.
</P>
<P>
   He said those concerns will be brought out at a meeting Tuesday
of the Senate's racing, gaming and wagering committee.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate, controlled by Republicans, must confirm Buley's
nomination.
</P>
<P>
   The resident of the Albany suburb of Slingerlands could not be
immediately reached for comment Monday on her nomination.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
