<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italian Mother Rues Exile in Kuwait  </HEADLINE>
By DIANA ELIAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUWAIT (AP) -- An Italian woman who took refuge with her two
daughters at Kuwait's Italian embassy after court rulings gave
custody rights to their father said Monday she wants to go home
with her girls.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope that in a short time we will be in Italy,'' Stefania,
33, told The Associated Press at the embassy. She spoke on the
condition only her first name would be used.
</P>
<P>
   Stefania accused her ex-husband of abusing her and her daughters
-- a charge the man, who holds Egyptian and Italian nationalities,
has denied. She said that although she loves Kuwait, where she has
lived for 12 years, she wants to live in Italy, ''where women are
protected by law and where we have the same rights as men.''
</P>
<P>
   The family's story has riveted Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Stefania and her husband, who is 20 years her senior, divorced
last year. In January, three weeks after a court placed her in her
father's custody, Stefania's eldest daughter fled to the embassy.
Stefania and her younger daughter joined the older girl this
weekend after a court awarded custody of the second girl to the
father.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was violent, he didn't respect me as a woman, and he tried
to strangle me once,'' Stefania told the AP. She said he also
punched Erica, 13, in the chest, hit her on the face and locked her
up at home.
</P>
<P>
   The former husband, who spoke on condition of anonymity, denied
he abused Stefania and the girls. He accused his ex-wife of trying
''to remove the role of the father from the lives of his
children.''
</P>
<P>
   In a statement published in the Al-Rai Al-Amm daily on Monday,
the father, who is a lawyer, said the courts believe it is not in
the interest of the Muslim girls to grow up in a ''Western
environment with different customs.'' He called on the government
to enable him to take his girls with him if he leaves Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   Stefania said she converted to Islam three years after the
couple married, but her ex-husband wants ''other people to think
I'm not a good Muslim'' so he can have the girls. She has turned
down her ex-husband's proposal that she keep the girls on weekdays
and give them to him on weekends. Stefania said her ex-husband
plans to go to Egypt this summer and take the girls with him.
</P>
<P>
   The older daughter, who appeared briefly to be photographed with
her mother and sister, said she wants to go to Italy and does not
want to live with her father because he beat her. The thin girl
with long black hair has been taking her school exams at the
embassy.
</P>
<P>
   A high-ranking Italian diplomat was dispatched here earlier this
year in an attempt to solve the problem, but Kuwaiti officials and
Italian diplomats have refused to comment on the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-12-00 1812 </TRAILER>
