<HEADLINE> Fourth poll finds Hillary Clinton-Lazio race tight  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A fourth statewide poll in less than three
weeks has found Hillary Rodham Clinton in a close race in New York
with her new Republican opponent for the U.S. Senate, Rep. Rick
Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   The CBS News/New York Times poll out Monday had Clinton with a
very slight lead over the little-known congressman from Long
Island. Clinton was backed by 44 percent of likely voters surveyed
to 39 percent for Lazio. Seventeen percent were undecided.
</P>
<P>
   A CBS News/New York Times poll out in April had Clinton leading
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, 49 percent to 41 percent, with 10 percent
undecided. Giuliani quit the race May 19 to deal with his prostate
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The new telephone poll of 1,187 likely voters was conducted June
4-10 and has a margin of error of plus of minus 3 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   On May 25, the Zogby International Group had the race a
statistical dead heat with Clinton at 46 percent and Lazio at 44
percent.
</P>
<P>
   On June 4, a poll conducted by Blum &AMP; Weprin for the New York
Daily News and cable television's New York 1 all-news channel
reported Clinton with a slight, 46 percent to 42 percent, lead over
Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   On June 7, the Quinnipiac University Polling Institute had
Clinton and Lazio tied, at 44 percent each.
</P>
</TEXT>
