<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Government rests tax case against Pirro  </HEADLINE>
By JIM FITZGERALD
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.Y. (AP) - Federal prosecutors wrapped up their
tax evasion case against Albert Pirro on Monday with more of the
stunning numbers that have defined the trial, including $1 million
in unreported income and a checking account overdraft that topped
$100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Cathy Seibel methodically attacked the
defense team's cross-examination of an Internal Revenue Service
agent, then rested her case and fought off a motion to dismiss the
indictment.
</P>
<P>
   The defense is scheduled to call its first witness on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The IRS agent, John Dennehy, said that between 1992 and 1995
alone, Pirro, husband of Westchester District Attorney Jeanine
Pirro, had more than $1 million in unreported income, representing
38 percent of his intake. Most of it showed up as business
deductions instead of personal spending, thereby reducing his tax
payment.
</P>
<P>
   ''Where did the money go that didn't go to Uncle Sam?'' Seibel
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ''Into Mr. Pirro's pocket,'' Dennehy said.
</P>
<P>
   In his fifth day on the witness stand, Dennehy testified that 69
percent of all the American Express charges on Pirro's various
business and personal cards - nearly $300,000 - were for personal
items.
</P>
<P>
   ''How much did Al Pirro pay from his personal funds?'' Seibel
asked.
</P>
<P>
   ''Zero,'' Dennehy said, testifying that it was all paid - and
deducted - by his businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Hammering the point, Seibel asked, ''Who took the trips? ... Who
got the clothes from Barneys? ... Who went on the Cunard Lines?''
</P>
<P>
   It was Albert Pirro, his wife and their children, Dennehy said.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, he said, Pirro spent $61,059 on personal items at the
Westchester Country Club, but not a cent of his own money.
</P>
<P>
   Seibel brought out that Pirro had apparently ironclad overdraft
protection on his personal account, often going five figures into
the red and at least once into six figures; she displayed for the
jury a bank statement that showed a deficit of $100,313.66.
</P>
<P>
   The defense has claimed that Pirro often used business checks
for personal spending when he didn't have enough cash in his
account.
</P>
<P>
   Over defense objections, Dennehy said he believed that Pirro
would still be writing off his $123,000 Ferrari and his $45,000
home security gates as business expenses if he weren't under
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Defense lawyer Robert Giuffra suggested last week that the gates
were legitimate business expenses because they were needed for
Jeanine Pirro's security. Seibel brought out Monday - before
Giuffra objected - that the Pirros had bought a pool, awnings for
their home and several luxury cars between the time they first said
they needed security and the time they installed the gates.
</P>
<P>
   The defense did have some victories Monday:
</P>
<P>
   -Giuffra made the point that only about 5 percent of all the
business deductions taken by Pirro's companies were challenged.
</P>
<P>
   ''In my book, being right 95 percent of the time, that's pretty
good,'' Giuffra said.
</P>
<P>
   -The IRS agent revised downward his figure on how much tax went
unpaid - $412,518 instead of $413,004.
</P>
<P>
   -And the judge refused to allow into evidence Albert Pirro's law
school transcript from 1974, which the prosecution hoped would show
that Pirro was not ''a layman'' when it came to understanding
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Pirro, asked outside court how he did in his tax law classes,
said, ''Obviously, not good enough.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
