<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State orders reform expanded into poor middle, high schools  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - It's hard enough to revamp an elementary
school from the ground up. Now urban superintendents face the
daunting task of instituting wholesale change in middle and high
schools.
</P>
<P>
   The state Board of Education last week adopted new regulations
forcing New Jersey's 30 so-called special needs school districts to
scrap educational plans in their secondary schools and replace them
with new ones.
</P>
<P>
   State officials defend the new mandate as necessary to improve
the poor schools' failing academic performance.
</P>
<P>
   But local school officials and state critics say the poor
schools already have enough to do. They also say so-called whole
school reform in the higher grades has not been thoroughly
researched.
</P>
<P>
   The new mandate also runs afoul of a 1998 state Supreme Court
ruling that ordered changes only in elementary schools, critics
charge.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever is right, the new mandate is expected to usher in a new
way of thinking about education from pre-school to 12th grade in
the special needs schools.
</P>
<P>
   There are several models employing various methods under the
overall umbrella of whole school reform. For example, the state's
favored model for elementary schools, Success for All, stresses
small class sizes, intense tutoring in reading, staff retraining,
and innovative budgeting.
</P>
<P>
   Local school administrators, faculty and parents work together
to choose and implement a specific model for their school.
</P>
<P>
   In its 1998 ruling, the court ordered the special needs schools
to implement whole school reform in all elementary schools. It's
considered one of the most far reaching reform experiments in the
nation.
</P>
<P>
   However, the court stopped short of requiring it in middle and
high schools, noting academic research was incomplete at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Education Commissioner Barbara Anderson said national
research has come far in two years. But she conceded that it is not
yet complete.
</P>
<P>
   ''While we believe more research needs to be done, we believe
it's important for the work at the elementary level to move
forward,'' she said. ''There are some promising models at the
secondary level.''
</P>
<P>
   ''As the research base broadens, we'll learn more about them,
about their strengths and weaknesses,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The state wants to be a step ahead of the research to prevent
any academic drop-off from occurring when elementary school
students graduate from their innovative programs to underperforming
middle schools, she said.
</P>
<P>
   But David Sciarra of the Education Law Center, which sued the
staff on behalf of poor school pupils, said it is premature for the
state to order such a massive retooling.
</P>
<P>
   Special needs middle and high schools must still implement a
menu of supplemental programs as well as rigorous curriculum
standards previously ordered by the court, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It makes no sense to add on yet another requirement,
particularly one on which there is absolutely no research produced
by the state showing its effectiveness,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also quarreled with the state's timeline. Schools must submit
their reform proposals to the state by January 2001, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Giving schools only seven months to do this is ludicrous.
There's no time to research the programs, their own needs, develop
plans, get a buy-in from teachers, and gets parents on board,''
Sciarra said.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson said the special needs school officials should not be
surprised. The state has been warning them for months that a
mandate was coming soon, she said. In fact, about one-third of the
100 secondary schools in the 30 poor districts have already
implemented some form of whole school reform on a voluntary basis,
she noted.
</P>
<P>
   Still, two special needs superintendents, including one who
jump-started the state's mandate in his higher grades, were not
impressed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whole school reform is a fiasco, a joke,'' said Ronald Larkin
of the New Brunswick school district.
</P>
<P>
   He complained that the state rushes local schools into proposing
new programs, then delays approving them.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everything is hurry up and wait,'' he said. ''It's delay,
underfund, delay, underfund. The frustration level is sky high.''
</P>
<P>
   Larkin said local officials chose a particular type of reform
because it was ''least disruptive and least harmful'' to the
students' routine.
</P>
<P>
   Millville Superintendent Larry Miller said he is dreading
expanding whole school reform into his upper grades, given the
state's record helping him institute it in the district's
elementary schools.
</P>
<P>
   ''The state ought to listen to the districts,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
