<DOCNO> APW20000612.0119 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Argentina Sorry for Nazi Harboring  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Fulfilling a promise he made last month,
President Fernando de la Rua of Argentina said Monday a main focus
of his U.S. visit will be to seek forgiveness for his country's
role in providing sanctuary to Nazis following World War II.
</P>
<P>
   He said in an interview an apology is appropriate because
''common Nazi criminals had found refuge in Argentina, and some
Jews were not given all the necessary facilities to emigrate to our
country.''
</P>
<P>
   De la Rua will meet Tuesday with President Clinton and also will
carry his message of forgiveness to the Holocaust Museum in
Washington, where a ceremony is planned. In addition, he will meet
with Jewish leaders.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to convey a message for the dignity and equality of all
human being and especially to Jews and all those who have suffered
persecution in Nazi Germany,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Jewish organizations welcomed de la Rua's remarks, but said they
wanted to see him take action to apprehend those who have committed
crimes against Jews and are still at large.
</P>
<P>
   ''Certainly it's welcome that de la Rua has reached out to the
Jewish community to acknowledge the harboring of the Nazi
criminal,'' said Malcolm Hoenlein of the Conference of Presidents
of Major American Jewish Organizations. ''I hope fully this will
transfer into action to finding those who are alive and at large.''
</P>
<P>
   Abraham Foxman, national director of the Anti-Defamation League,
said: ''Going public about harboring war criminals is important. As
important as that is, it is really important to see when and if the
Argentine government can bring to justice those who perpetrated the
bombing of the Jewish community center and embassy. There still is
no closure on that.''
</P>
<P>
   A 1992 bombing of the Israeli Embassy in Buenos Aires killed 29
people. Two years later, an attack on a Jewish community center in
the Argentine capital claimed 86 people.
</P>
<P>
   In Buenos Aires recently, de la Rua held a luncheon in honor of
Holocaust survivors.
</P>
<P>
   At a speech last month to mark the 57th anniversary of the April
19-May 16, 1943, Warsaw Uprising by Jews, de la Rua said Argentina
had to come to grips with its past, which included harboring wanted
Nazi war criminals for decades. Some may still be at large, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1960, Israeli agents abducted Adolph Eichmann, a chief
architect of the Holocaust, from his hide-out in Buenos Aires.
</P>
<P>
   And in 1998, Argentine authorities arrested Dinko Sakic,
one-time commander at Croatia's Jasenovac concentration camp, who
had been living peacefully in Argentina. He was extradited to
Croatia, where last year he was sentenced to 20 years in prison for
war crimes.
</P>
<P>
   Argentine researchers reported in November 1998 that they had
found proof that former Argentine President Juan Peron encouraged
fleeing Nazi war criminals to seek asylum in his country after
World War II. Peron was president between 1945 and 1955.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Israeli-based groups say that the number of Jews
purged during the anti-left campaign of the 1976-83 military
dictatorship was disproportionately high.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of the number of Jews who vanished during that period
range as high as 2,000, and Israel has asked the de la Rua
government to investigate. Argentina is home to about 300,000 Jews,
the second largest Jewish community in the Americas.
</P>
<P>
   De la Rua credited his democratic predecessors for significantly
improving the country's human rights record. He noted that his
immediate predecessor, Carlos Menem, ordered a full investigation
in 1992 into Argentina's role in sheltering Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   He said Argentina has come a long way from the period when
rights abuses occurred routinely.
</P>
<P>
   Nowadays, he said, ''there is a law against racism.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: State Department:
http://www.state.gov/www/regions/wha/index.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
