<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 19:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State urged to restore recycling funds after declining rates released </HEADLINE>
By Nina Rizzo
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The Association of New Jersey Recyclers is
asking the state Legislature to restore a multimillion dollar fund
that rewarded towns for documenting how many bottles, cans and
newspapers were recycled.
</P>
<P>
   The move came after the state released figures that show New
Jersey's overall recycling rate has declined 9 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The state Department of Environmental Protection reported that
the amount of waste recycled dropped from 61 percent to 55.5
percent between 1997 and 1998, the year for which the latest
figures were available.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's a major jump backward,'' said Marie Kruzan, executive
director of the recycling association. ''I'm not looking forward to
the 1999 figure because I think it's going to be worse.''
</P>
<P>
   When the state enacted a mandatory recycling law in 1987, it
also created a $1.50-per-ton tax on waste disposal to support the
Recycling Tonnage Grant Program. The program had a $9 million fund,
on average, that municipal and county recycling coordinators could
tap into to supplement the cost of education campaigns and other
efforts. The amount of money each coordinator received was
dependent upon the number of recyclables documented.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a very good carrot,'' said Kruzan. ''There was an
infrastructure in place to make this work.''
</P>
<P>
   The tax, however, lapsed in 1997 and the fund is expected to dry
up by the end of the year, said Guy Watson, chief of the DEP's
Office of Recycling and Planning.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the last year the tax was collected, the fund reached
$12 million. About 60 percent of that money went to municipalities
($5.4 million) and counties ($1.5 million). The rest was used for
state-funded recycling efforts, Watson said.
</P>
<P>
   Vineland recycling coordinator Barbara Panzino said that town
typically received about $75,000 from the fund. She is pushing for
restoration of the tax so Vineland can continue promote recycling,
buy new buckets and pay for code enforcement officers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Some people do it because it's the right thing and others do
it because they have to,'' said Panzino. ''That's why we're seeing
the drop.''
</P>
<P>
   DEP spokesman Peter Page said the 1998 figures are incomplete
because more than 50 towns did not report recycling rates.
</P>
<P>
   ''When towns stopped getting grants, they stopped reporting
their numbers,'' said Page. ''Towns don't have the direct financial
incentives they had three years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Alan Augustine, R-Union, introduced a bill in
January that would create a similar fund, but it has yet to be
considered by the Assembly Solid Waste Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Augustine said the fund needs to be restored if the state wants
to maintain the highest recycling rate in the country, and meet
even more ambitious goals. The DEP wants to increase the state's
recycling rate from 60 percent to 65 percent by Dec. 31, he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the Solid Waste Committee chair, Assemblyman John
Rooney, R-Bergen, doesn't comprehend the importance of spending
money on recycling education programs.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no way I'm going to impose another tax,'' said Rooney,
who is also mayor of Northvale. ''If local officials can't get
people to recycle, shame on them.
</P>
<P>
   ''In my town we tell the garbage men to shake the bags. If they
hear bottles or cans or see newspapers, leave it there. That's the
best education program you can give to residents. It doesn't have
to happen twice,'' Rooney said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Morris, who teaches the economics component of the recycling
coordinator certification course offered by Rutgers University,
said the fund helped New Jersey create a model program.
</P>
<P>
   ''We still have the most comprehensive program in the nation,''
said Morris. ''But for recyclers to have their message heard, they
need a statewide commitment of resources.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't matter if it's a Hershey bar or a Web site, if you
don't promote it you have to expect that awareness or participation
will decline.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   www.recyclenj.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
