<HEADLINE> Diallo parents to attend Springsteen concert  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - The parents of Amadou Diallo were to attend
Bruce Springsteen's concert at Madison Square Garden Monday to
thank him for writing a song about their son's death at the hands
of four police officers, a family friend said.
</P>
<P>
   Saikou and Kadiatou Diallo also will extend an invitation to
Springsteen to visit with the city's black community, said the
friend, who declined to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   Spokespeople for Springsteen did not return repeated telephone
messages Monday for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Monday starts Springsteen's 10-show run at the Garden. It was
unclear whether he would perform the song about Diallo, called
''American Skin (41 Shots).''
</P>
<P>
   Springsteen introduced the new song last week during a concert
in Atlanta with his E Street Band. The song, which does not mention
Diallo by name, opens up with these words: ''41 shots, 41 shots.''
That's the number of bullets fired at Diallo by the officers on
Feb. 4, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The 22-year-old West African immigrant was mortally wounded as
he stood in the vestibule of his Bronx home when police mistook his
wallet for a weapon. The four officers involved in the shooting
were acquitted of murder earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   The song's refrain contains the line: ''Is this your wallet? Is
this your life?'' At another point, Springsteen reportedly sings,
''You can get killed just for living in your American skin.''
</P>
<P>
   The Patrolmen's Benevolent Association, which represents the
city's 27,000 police officers, has urged its members not to attend
or work overtime security detail at Springsteen's Garden concerts.
</P>
<P>
   Police Lt. Eric Adams, of 100 Blacks in Law Enforcement Who
Care, said his group supports Springsteen and is upset that few
black artists have used their talents to support the Diallo family.
</P>
<P>
   ''We commend Bruce Springsteen and we believe that he is
courageous in the position that he is taking,'' Adams said in a
news conference before the concert.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Website for Springsteen fans: www.luckytown.org.
</P>
<P>
   Patrolmen's Benevolent Association: www.nycpba.org.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
