<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 19:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> High court scheduled to rule on mall access  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - The state Supreme Court is scheduled to
release its decision Tuesday on whether political groups can have
unfettered access to shopping malls.
</P>
<P>
   The case stems from a 1996 lawsuit filed after a Secaucus mall
required the Green Party of New Jersey to buy a $1 million
insurance policy before it could distribute leaflets.
</P>
<P>
   Green Party members contend that the insurance policy was
restrictive and its $665 price tag cost them their right to free
speech. A trial court agreed. But in August an appeals court said
mall owners were justified in requiring the insurance policy.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the justices rule, their decision will have to do with
much more than just the case of the Green Party against mall owner
Hartz Mountain Industries, said lawyer Frank Askin, an attorney
with the Rutgers Law School Constitutional Litigation Clinic.
</P>
<P>
   ''It has to do with the right of free speech at these ubiquitous
state shopping malls,'' said Askin, who argued the case for the
Green Party.
</P>
<P>
   Mall at Mill Creek managers require every group that comes into
the mall to get the insurance policy, according to lawyer Curtis L.
Michael. But after the appellate ruling, mall managers have
developed several options, including a $250 permit, Michael told
the court during oral arguments in March.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court ruled in 1994 that although shopping malls and
other similar marketplaces are privately owned, they can be
considered public forums, Askin said.
</P>
<P>
   In that earlier decision, the court said groups could use the
malls much as they would public places like town squares, Askin
said. The court also said the mall owners could make reasonable
requirements of the groups.
</P>
<P>
   ''This case will now define what reasonable requirements are,''
Askin said.
</P>
<P>
   Askin said the opinion will be carefully read since it comes
from a court supervised by Chief Justice Deborah T. Poritz and
several other justices, all appointed recently by Gov. Christie
Whitman.
</P>
<P>
   ''This will be the first decision by the new Poritz court on a
significant issue of free speech under the state constitution,''
Askin said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It really will be the first indication of where this court is
going on these issues,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
