<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rebels Attack Sierra Leone Town  </HEADLINE>
By CLARENCE ROY-MACAULAY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WATERLOO, Sierra Leone (AP) -- Pro-government troops said they
repelled a fierce rebel attack against a front-line town, and a
Sierra Leonean government militia handed over dozens of child
fighters to aid workers Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting raged for three hours in Lunsar, about 45 miles
east of the capital, Lt. Edmond Bangura told journalists Monday.
The troops eventually drove the rebels off.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear whether there were any casualties. Bangura said
the soldiers and pro-government militiamen often fired on each
other and found it difficult to determine their own troops from the
rebels.
</P>
<P>
   Fighters on both sides wear a hodgepodge of civilian clothing,
military uniforms and traditional garb that sometimes includes
charms, headbands and fetish necklaces.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was confusion everywhere,'' Bangura said.
</P>
<P>
   Also Monday, the Vatican news agency MISNA cited local sources
as saying state helicopters ''intercepted'' a rebel contingent
nearly a week earlier at Kabata Junction, some five miles from the
government-held town of Port Loko. More than 100 rebels were killed
in the attack, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The report could not be independently confirmed. Government
officials, who are usually quick to take credit for battlefield
successes, said they were not aware of the alleged incident.
</P>
<P>
   Lunsar was retaken by government forces twice last week, nearly
a month after the rebel Revolutionary United Front captured it. The
rebels reignited Sierra Leone's civil war in early May, kidnapping
U.N. troops and launching an offensive that at one point reportedly
came within 25 miles of Freetown.
</P>
<P>
   The rebels have killed tens of thousands of people and committed
countless other atrocities, including lopping off civilians' hands,
legs and other appendages.
</P>
<P>
   In another development Monday, the pro-government Civil Defense
Force, a militia of traditional hunters also known as the Kamajors,
handed over to aid workers 138 children -- mostly soldiers but also
girls and boys forced by rebels to become porters and sex slaves.
</P>
<P>
   The children, aged eight to 16, were taken into the militia's
custody in front-line towns like Lunsar, Civil Defense Force
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Jordanian U.N. peacekeepers escorted the children from the town
of Masiaka to a temporary tent camp in the government stronghold of
Waterloo, 10 miles from Freetown.
</P>
<P>
   There they were being clothed, fed and interviewed to determine
whether to place them in camps for ex-child combatants or returned
to their families, UNICEF official Roisin de Burca said.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the young girls told journalists of being forced to
become ''wives,'' or sex slaves, of rebel leaders before escaping
or being captured in battles with the Civil Defense Force.
</P>
<P>
   Mariama Mansaray, 15, said she was held as a sex slave by the
rebels in various bush camps for four years before escaping about a
month ago and making her way by road to Masiaka.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to return to school,'' Mansaray said.
</P>
<P>
   Mohamed Conteh, 16, said he had fought with an assault rifle for
years as a member of the Civil Defense Force, and had ''killed
anyone, whether RUF or civilians, if I had to.''
</P>
<P>
   Another child fighter, 12-year-old Mohamed Kargbo, said he was
abducted from his family last June and accompanied the rebels on
raids in which they looted villages.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were rioters. Everything we could find, we took to the
bush,'' Kargbo said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
