<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former parole commissioner indicted on perjury charges  </HEADLINE>
By TOM HAYS
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) - A former state parole commissioner lied to a
grand jury investigating allegations that the office of Gov. George
Pataki sought the early release of violent felons in exchange for
campaign contributions, authorities charged Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A 15-page indictment unsealed in Brooklyn federal court charges
the defendant, Leo Levy, with six counts of perjury and one count
of obstruction of justice.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998 grand jury testimony, Levy admitted he violated his oath
of office by letting ''impermissible factors'' influence his
decision to parole armed robber John Kim, whose parents had
contributed to Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had a predisposition to consider the case favorably,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But authorities allege Levy - an appointee of former Gov. Mario
Cuomo who left the parole board in 1998 - also sought to protect
himself and the Pataki administration by falsely accusing mid-level
bureaucrats of illicitly lobbying for the release of Kim at a 1996
hearing. Records show one of those bureaucrats was never there.
</P>
<P>
   Levy, 57, who faces up to 10 years in prison if convicted, was
expected to surrender later this week. His attorney, Brian Mumford,
did not return a call for comment.
</P>
<P>
   The indictment stems from an ongoing grand jury investigation of
possible corruption at the state Board of Parole.
</P>
<P>
   So far, two other parole officials have been convicted of lying
to investigators. A Republican fundraiser, Yung Soo Yoo, also is
facing trial next month on charges he illegally solicited
contributions from members of the Korean-American community who had
children in prison.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation also has focused on a top Pataki aide, Patrick
Donohue. But no one close to the governor, including Donohue, his
campaign finance director, has been charged.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki spokesman Mike McKeon had no comment on Monday. Said
Parole Department spokesman Tom Grant: ''We're confident that the
parole board handled this case in an appropriate matter.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators launched their probe after a Korean man
went to police claiming Donohue had failed to deliver on a
guarantee to free his son for $20,000 in donations.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have said they found documents indicating that at
Donohue's prompting, Pataki's New York City staff contacted parole
officials about three Korean-American inmates whose families made
sizable campaign contributions to the governor's 1994 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In one case, parole official Sean McSherry led the three-member
parole panel - including Levy - that met with Kim, then 21, at an
upstate prison in April 1996.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Kim had served the minimum four years of a
4-to-12-year sentence for three armed robberies in Queens. The
board unanimously ordered Kim's release over the objections of
Queens prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, a Brooklyn jury found McSherry guilty of lying to the
grand jury. He was sentenced to two years in prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-12-00 1921 </TRAILER>
