<DOCNO> APW20000612.0130 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NBA Finals Notebook  </HEADLINE>
By CHRIS SHERIDAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- If Shaquille O'Neal keeps missing free
throws, he can expect to be fouled intentionally for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   There's no rule against it, and there won't be one any time
soon.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're not planning to rush out and enact some Hack-a-Shaq
antidote. We've been very slow to rush to make changes in our
game,'' NBA commissioner David Stern said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Hack-a-Shaq strategy calls for intentionally fouling O'Neal
on every Los Angeles Lakers' possession late in games -- but not in
the final two minutes -- to put O'Neal on the free throw line.
</P>
<P>
   The Indiana Pacers used it in Game 2 of the Finals, sending
O'Neal to the line an NBA-record 39 times, and the Portland Trail
Blazers tried it in the Western Conference finals, forcing Shaq to
shoot 25 free throws in the fourth quarter of Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers and Trail Blazers lost those games.
</P>
<P>
   ''It doesn't work,'' O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   Although it hasn't worked yet, Indiana coach Larry Bird has not
ruled out employing Hack-a-Shaq again if the circumstances call for
it. Ideally, the Pacers would hope for O'Neal to make about half
his foul shots, giving Indiana a chance to limit the Lakers to one
point per possession.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacers then, in theory, could get two or three points per
possession and cut into a Lakers' lead. In Game 2, the Pacers got
within three -- but no closer -- by using the Hack-a-Shaq.
</P>
<P>
   In the final two minutes of games, the strategy must be
abandoned because of the NBA rule that provides for one free throw
-- plus retaining possession of the ball -- if a foul is committed
against a player who does not have the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our feeling is that it's a strategy that these two teams
employed, so far without great success, and for us to be running to
create some rule because of that doesn't seem logical,'' deputy
commissioner Russ Granik said.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it became a commonplace thing, then we might have to look
at it. But when we met (last week) with competition committee and
the coaches, there was absolutely no discussion on the subject,''
Granik said. ''I don't see any point in addressing how we might fix
it until we reach a conclusion that it needs to be fixed.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, a career 53 percent free throw shooter, went 3-for-13
from the line in Game 3 after going 18-for-39 in Game 2 and 1-for-6
in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   RULES CHANGES: The NBA plans to implement one significant rule
change for next season, reducing a team's timeouts from seven to
six.
</P>
<P>
   Teams currently are limited to four full timeouts in the fourth
quarter and three during the final two minutes. Those limits also
will be reduced by one.
</P>
<P>
   The change is aimed at preventing fourth quarters from lasting
too long, such as the 54-minute fourth quarter in Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ''It may take a while for the coaches to get used to,'' Granik
said.
</P>
<P>
   The rule change was approved last week by the competition
committee and is expected to be approved by the league's Board of
Governors in July.
</P>
<P>
   To placate the coaches, two other rules will be adjusted. Teams
will now be able to advance the ball to midcourt by calling a
20-second timeout after a made basket, and they will be able to
inbound into the backcourt instead of being limited to the
frontcourt.
</P>
<P>
   ''The coaches were ready to give up a timeout, but they wanted
to make it a little easier to inbound the ball because that's often
when you need one of your timeouts,'' Granik said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   MUSTN'T SEE TV: There won't be as many Saturday games on
national television next season. There were 10 this season with low
viewership numbers that dragged down the league's overall ratings --
21 percent during the regular season and 12 percent in the first
three rounds of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   For the first two games of the Finals, national ratings are off
5 percent from last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''This past year we had some problems in the regular season,''
Stern said. ''Those Saturday night games, I didn't know they were
on some nights. I forgot.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need some more regular programming and we need less on
Saturdays. Outside of the playoffs, people don't associate NBA
basketball with late Saturday afternoons. It's a Sunday sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Current plans call for NBC to televise five Saturday night games
in succession next season, perhaps in late December or January.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   NOT NAMED MNBA: Granik said the NBA's new minor league is
slated to begin play in November 2001, and will be called the
National Basketball Developmental League, or NBDL.
</P>
<P>
   Players must be 20 years old to play unless they were drafted by
an NBA team and then cut before reaching that age.
</P>
<P>
   The league will be centrally run, and teams will be placed in
cities with populations of 750,000 or less with arenas that seat
6,000-10,000 fans. There will be 8-10 teams in the first season,
all in cities located in somewhat close proximity to one another.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll probably try to stay in one geographic region, but we're
not sure where yet,'' Granik said.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   THE BIG MUMBLE: Poking fun at O'Neal's low-volume voice, a
reporter at Monday's news conference mumbled unintelligibly into a
microphone pretending to ask O'Neal a question.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal took the bait and brought the house down.
</P>
<P>
   ''I DON'T TALK LIKE THIS. SORRY,'' he boomed into his own
microphone, drawing howls of appreciative laughter. ''Most of you
guys who've been watching me know I'm a smooth, mellow guy.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   CYBERDAVE BITES TONGUE: In one of the day's biggest surprises,
Stern used the word ''Internet'' only twice during a nearly
hour-long news conference.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
