<HEADLINE> Mets' Joneses Switch Places  </HEADLINE>
By RONALD BLUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Keeping up with their Joneses, the Mets are
sending Bobby J. (the right-hander) to the minors for 10 days and
bringing up Bobby M. (the left-hander).
</P>
<P>
   Bobby J. is just 1-3 with a 10.19 ERA in 10 starts, allowing 38
runs and 50 hits in 32 2-3 innings. Because he has more than five
seasons of major league service, New York needed his permission to
option him to Triple-A Norfolk.
</P>
<P>
   Because of days off, the Mets don't need a fifth starter until
June 23 against Pittsburgh, and New York promised to bring back
Bobby J. to pitch that night.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes you have to swallow your pride and do what's best
for you and what's best for the organization,'' Bobby J. said.
''There have been a lot of restless times and sleepless nights
figuring out what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   He gave up seven runs and nine hits during 4 2-3 innings against
the Yankees in Saturday's 13-5 loss and hasn't made it past the
sixth inning all year. The roster moves are effective Tuesday,
before the Mets' game at the Chicago Cubs.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think I have a long way to go,'' Bobby J. said Monday.
''I think there is a significant difference between my first few
starts off the DL and the Yankees start. I thought I had pretty
good stuff in the Yankees game. Sometimes guys hit good pitches. A
couple of things go my way and it's a different situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who struck out Ken Griffey Jr. and Mark McGwire in the
1997 All-Star game, has just one win since April 17, 1999, beating
Arizona on May 19, his first start after a stint on the disabled
list caused by a calf problem.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets were off Monday and are scheduled to be off Thursday
and next Monday. For the next 10 days, they'll need just four
starters.
</P>
<P>
   ''Just the fact that I'm struggling like I have, I need to get
innings,'' Bobby J. said. ''It's not going to do me one bit of good
to go the bullpen and pitch every sixth or seventh day. I'm not
going to get straightened out that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby M., acquired during the offseason from Colorado for Masato
Yoshii, becomes another left-hander in a bullpen that already
includes lefties John Franco, Dennis Cook and Rich Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby M. is 6-3 with a 4.18 ERA in 12 starts for Norfolk,
allowing 35 runs and 70 hits in 75 1-3 innings. Mets general
manager Steve Phillips said New York wants to ''get a taste of what
he can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Phillips said sending Bobby J. to Norfolk shouldn't be
interpreted as a demotion.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's for a finite period of time and an agreed upon period of
time,'' Phillips said. ''We're absolutely going to bring him back
to start the game on the 23rd.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby J. is confident he can bounce back.
</P>
<P>
   ''I haven't lost my mental edge,'' he said. ''When you go out
there doubting yourself, you're beat before you go out there, and
at that point, you go on to do other things.''
</P>
<P>
Notes: The Mets-Yankees' game at Shea Stadium on July 9 may be
moved from 1:10 p.m. to 8:05 p.m. so ESPN can televise it. Sunday's
rainout at Yankee Stadium could be made up as a day-night
doubleheader on July 8, with the day game at Shea Stadium and the
night game at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-12-00 1954 </TRAILER>
