<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 20:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pirates' Giles Gets $45M Contract  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN ROBINSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Brian Giles might be the first $45 million
bargain in Pittsburgh Pirates history.
</P>
<P>
   Giles, who went into Monday night's game against Atlanta leading
the NL with 60 RBIs, will average $7.5 million a season under the
terms of $45 million, six-year contract he signed May 19.
</P>
<P>
   The contract's total value was reported previously, but not
Giles' per-year salary, which could jump, with incentives, to as
much as $9 million by 2005.
</P>
<P>
   Of the $45 million, $12.5 million will be deferred at 5 percent
interest until 2006, the year after the richest contract in the
Pirates' 113-year history expires.
</P>
<P>
   Giles' deal dwarfs the $24 million, four-year contract signed
last year by first baseman Kevin Young, previously the biggest in
club history.
</P>
<P>
   However, based on Dodgers outfielder Shawn Green's $84 million,
six-year contract and the $57 million, six-year million deal signed
recently by Cardinals outfielder Jim Edmonds, the contract could be
a bargain if Giles continues to produce as he has in his first 1{
Pirates seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Formerly a platoon outfielder with Cleveland, Giles hit .315
with 39 homers and 115 RBIs before missing the final 11 games last
season with a fractured finger. He has been one of baseball's most
consistent hitters this season, batting .335 with 19 homers and 60
RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   Giles' new contract replaces the deal he signed when he was with
Cleveland and was worth $1.75 million this season, $2.55 million in
2001 and a club-option year worth $3,625,000 in 2002. That contract
would have increased $200,000 per year in 2001 and 2002 with 600
plate appearances the previous season.
</P>
<P>
   In his new contract, the 29-year-old Giles received an $8
million signing bonus, with $5.5 million deferred, and will make $3
million this season, with $1 million deferred.
</P>
<P>
   He will make $6 million in 2001 (with $2 million deferred), and
$7 million each in 2002, 2003, 2004 and 2005 (with $4 million of
his 2002 salary deferred).
</P>
<P>
   Giles' salaries would increase to:
</P>
<P>
   --$7.5 million in 2003 if he has been an All-Star in two of the
preceding three seasons, in 2004 if he has been an All-Star in two
preceding seasons; and in 2005 if he has been an All-Star in three
preceding seasons.
</P>
<P>
   --$8 million in 2003 for finishing in the top 10 in the NL MVP
voting in any preceding season or in the top 15 in any two
preceding seasons; or in 2004 for finishing the top 15 in the MVP
voting in two preceding seasons.
</P>
<P>
   --$8.5 million in 2004 for finishing in the top 10 in the MVP
voting in two preceding seasons; or in 2005 for finishing in the
top 15 in the MVP voting in three preceding seasons.
</P>
<P>
   --$9 million in 2005 for finishing in the top 10 in the MVP
voting in three preceding seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Giles also has a limited trade clause that allows him to
designate six teams each year he can be traded to.
</P>
<P>
   By deferring $12.5 million, Giles put the Pirates in a better
position to re-sign key players such as catcher Jason Kendall,
whose contract runs through 2001, and pitcher Todd Ritchie, a
15-game winner last season.
</P>
<P>
   Ritchie recently signed a $5.25 million, two-year extension that
runs through 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ''The big thing for me was to structure the deal so we can sign
Jason Kendall and Todd Ritchie, guys who are going to need new
deals,'' Giles said. ''This team needs to keep guys we can win
with.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-12-00 2011 </TRAILER>
