<HEADLINE> Brazil Police End Bus Standoff  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) -- Police ended a four-hour standoff
Monday by storming a city bus and fatally wounding a man who had
held passengers at gunpoint, but one hostage died during the
rescue.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't immediately clear if the 20-year-old woman was killed
by police or the assailant. Globo television news showed the
assailant with his gun to the head of a female hostage as a special
tactics police approached and opened fire.
</P>
<P>
   The man was wounded but still alive immediately after the police
stormed the bus. Crowds tried to attack him, but officers were able
to haul him away in a van.
</P>
<P>
   The assailant had boarded the bus hours earlier. During the
standoff, he fired his gun and threatened to kill his eight
hostages unless given money and grenades.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was horrible, horrible. I had to give him my money for him
not to kill me in the back seat,'' one hostage told Globo
television through a bus window after the police raid.
</P>
<P>
   The man was a robbery suspect, and police were following him
when he tried to escape by boarding the bus, according to reports.
Police blocked the bus's progress on a main road in Rio's upscale
Jardim Botanico district, next to the city's famous botanical
gardens, and the tense standoff ensued.
</P>
<P>
   As TV networks broadcast the standoff live, the man put the gun
in passengers' mouths and threatened to shoot. He fired out the
window and told one woman to lie down, then fired at the floor.
</P>
<P>
   According to initial reports the 17-year-old passenger who had
been told to lie down was killed or injured, but police later said
she was unharmed. Earlier, she had been forced to write in lipstick
on the window: ''He has a pact with the devil and showed me his arm
with the devil and a dagger.''
</P>
<P>
   Ranting and gesturing, the man reportedly demanded two grenades
and $550. He allowed three passengers to leave, but several women
still were visible through the bus windows.
</P>
<P>
   At one point he stuck his head out the window and shouted:
''I'll blow her head off. This is not a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Toward the end of the crisis, the suspect ordered the hostages
to the back of the bus, where he apparently threatened to kill
them. Police stormed the bus soon afterward.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-12-00 2014 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000612.0137 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pirates' Schmidt on DL  </HEADLINE>
By ALAN ROBINSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Jason Schmidt, expected to be the Pittsburgh
Pirates' No. 1 starter this season but only a two-game winner so
far, was placed on the disabled list Monday with more shoulder
problems.
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt spent two weeks on the disabled list in April with an
inflamed shoulder, an injury that had lingered since spring
training.
</P>
<P>
   The right-hander has not been especially effective since
returning from that layoff, allowing 45 hits and 25 earned runs in
34 1-3 innings in six starts while experiencing continued
discomfort in his shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Cam Bonifay said the problem is affecting ''the
command and control of his slider.''
</P>
<P>
   To replace Schmidt, right-hander Bronson Arroyo was recalled
from Triple-A Nashville and was scheduled to start Tuesday night
against Atlanta, his major league debut.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Schmidt -- the Pirates' key acquisition in the Denny
Neagle trade in 1996 -- is 2-5 with a 5.40 ERA and 41 walks in 63
1-3 innings after going 13-11 with a 4.19 ERA last year.
</P>
<P>
   Because the pain in Schmidt's shoulder has persisted almost
since the start of spring training, it is possible this stay on the
disabled list could be an extended one.
</P>
<P>
   The 27-year-old Schmidt is to be examined Wednesday in
Birmingham, Ala., by Dr. James Andrews, who has operated on
numerous pro athletes. Andrews specializes in reconstructive
surgery, and it is doubtful he would be examining Schmidt unless
there were concerns Schmidt's injury might be serious.
</P>
<P>
   ''I want to get a total checkup from him,'' Schmidt said Monday.
''He's the best in the business. I want him to look at it and see
what he thinks. I want to find out what is wrong once and for
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Schmidt's injury came just when the Pirates' starting pitching
seemed to be settling down after being uneven all season. Kris
Benson has made a succession of strong starts despite having only a
4-5 record, and Todd Ritchie has lost just twice in seven starts
since late April.
</P>
<P>
   The 23-year-old Arroyo has been the Pirates' most successful
minor league starter the last two seasons, going 15-4 at Double-A
Altoona and 0-2 at Nashville last season and 7-2 with a 3.86 ERA in
12 starts with the Sounds this season.
</P>
<P>
   A control pitcher, he usually does not throw more than 90 or 91
miles per hour, but walked a relatively low 58 in 153 innings in
Double-A last season. He has a 56-30 career minor league record
after being drafted in the third round of the 1995 June draft from
Hernando High School in Brooksville, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Arroyo will be the 20th pitcher used this season by the Pirates,
including catcher Keith Osik, who pitched one inning in a blowout
loss to St. Louis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-12-00 2018 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000612.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State agrees to tentative contract with a law enforcement union  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The state has agreed to a tentative contract
with a law enforcement union that includes a series of raises of at
least 3 percent a year, state officials announced Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The tentative contract with Council 82 of the American
Federation of State, County and Municipal Employees must still be
approved by the rank and file. The employees have worked without a
contract since April 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The deal includes a 3-percent raise retroactive to October,
another 3 percent retroactive to April, 3.5 percent more in April
2001, and 3.5 percent more in April 2002, according to state
officials.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement also calls for a $500 signing bonus and increases
in co-payments for office visits and prescription drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a fair contract that demonstrates our respect for the
important job that members of Council 82 perform for the taxpayers
of New York,'' said Governor George Pataki.
</P>
<P>
   Council 82 represents security officers on State University of
New York campuses, forest rangers, life guards and other personnel.
It covers workers in the state departments of correctional
services, mental health, mental retardation and development
disabilities, SUNY, environmental conservation and parks and
recreation.
</P>
<P>
   The union was usurped by New York State Correctional Officers
and Police Benevolent Association in 1999 as the bargaining unit
for state prison corrections officers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
