<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 20:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fire destroys old records, knocks out phone system in municipal building </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TENAFLY, N.J. (AP) - A fire in a storage room of Tenafly's
police, fire and municipal building destroyed years of old records
and knocked out the building's phone system Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A police dispatcher - the only person in the building - saw
smoke coming out of a ventilation shaft at about 3 a.m. and called
Cresskill's fire department because the building's electricity and
paging system had failed, Capt. Wayne Morrison said.
</P>
<P>
   The borough's volunteer fire department houses its equipment in
the same building that holds its government offices and 29-member
police force.
</P>
<P>
   The fire in the building's attic was declared under control
within an hour, but borough records that may have gone back 100
years were destroyed, including construction histories on
buildings, Health Department records and information on historical
buildings in town, Mayor Ann Moscovitz said.
</P>
<P>
   She said state officials will be coming there to decipher
exactly what's missing, but ''a lot of it looks as if it's pretty
well charred.''
</P>
<P>
   Fire officials believe a severe storm Sunday night caused either
a lightning strike or an electrical outage which led to the
building fire, Morrison said.
</P>
<P>
   The loss of telephone service forced police to route 911 calls
through Cresskill and communicate with each other through police
radio. Bergen County Police sent over a van with compatible police
radios, and dispatch operations were relocated in a trailer,
Morrison said.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone service in the borough administration building was
expected to be restored by Tuesday, but Morrison said police
telecommunications service would take longer to fix.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're looking at about a several months disruption of
service,'' Morrison said. ''We'll be working out of a trailer for
some time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
