<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ecuador Colonels Offer To Resign  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   QUITO, Ecuador (AP) -- Nine military leaders of an insurrection
that prompted the overthrow of President Jamil Mahuad offered to
resign their posts Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Army Col. Lucio Gutierrez said he made the decision, along with
six officers and two enlisted men, as ''a contribution to peace for
all Ecuadoreans.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with hundreds of Indians, Gutierrez led a cadre of
soldiers, mostly midlevel officers, in the Jan. 21, takeover of the
Congress building.
</P>
<P>
   Their declaration of a ''Parliament of the People'' to fight
corruption and end poverty prompted top military leaders to force
Mahuad from power.
</P>
<P>
   After recognizing a short-lived junta, the military high command
ceded control to Gustavo Noboa, the democratically elected vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   Military court proceedings were halted after Congress approved
Noboa's request to grant amnesty to the Indian and military
insurrectionists in the name of national reconciliation. But the
amnesty, approved May 31, did not rule out disciplinary action by
the military.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Minister Hugo Unda said last week that military
ringleaders in the uprising would be asked to resign voluntarily,
or would face forced discharge under military regulations.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen of Gutierrez's followers have said they will go to
court to fight efforts to oust them from the military ranks. Dozens
of other members of the armed forces face lesser disciplinary
action for their part in Mahuad's unconstitutional overthrow.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
