<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Self-appointed freshness police sues supermarket chain  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   GOSHEN, N.Y. (AP) - A couple years ago a supermarket chain
guaranteed its products' freshness and put their money where their
vow was.
</P>
<P>
   So five local men started cruising ShopRite stores in search of
items where the expiration date expired.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're saying they have a freshness guarantee,'' said
68-year-old John Pizza, a retired salesman turned un-fresh prince.
''We said, 'Well, let's see how fresh it is.'''
</P>
<P>
   He and four other men hit ShopRite stores throughout Orange
County. They say they found expired food every time - sometimes as
many as 40 items.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes ShopRite would pay the $1 bounty. Sometimes Pizza said
they wouldn't.
</P>
<P>
   Now he and the other un-freshmen have filed suit against
ShopRite's owners, Big V supermarkets, and the parent company,
Wakefern Food Corporation. Pizza, Michael Catanzaro, Ray Bowley,
Jeffrey Burfeindt, and Henry Williams claim ShopRite attempted to
defraud the public with its freshness claim and should pay them $5
million, according to the Middletown Times Herald-Record.
</P>
<P>
   ShopRite rejects the claim.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do believe the claims are without merit and we'll prevail
in court,'' said Alan Lewis, Big V's lawyer. He said he couldn't
discuss the details of the case because it's in litigation.
</P>
<P>
   Wakefern's spokeswoman, Karen Meleta, said, ''Big V and Wakefern
believe there is no basis to the claim.''
</P>
<P>
   ''What they're doing is consumer fraud,'' Pizza said. ''They're
endangering the public with these expired foods.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he has about 50 food items - from salmon to cottage
cheese - that he will bring into court if the case goes to trial.
</P>
<P>
   Pizza and his posse are representing themselves because lawyers
cost too much.
</P>
<P>
   He noted, however, that it's not illegal to sell most food past
its expiration date.
</P>
<P>
   ''They wouldn't be breaking any laws,'' said Pete Gregg, the
spokesman for the state Department of Agriculture and Markets, the
state agency that monitors supermarkets. Expiration dates are
''voluntarily imposed by the industry,'' he said. He noted, too,
that ShopRite has a good reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ''Expiration dates do not impact on safety,'' said Jill
Hollingsworth of the national Food Marketing Institute.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-12-00 2046 </TRAILER>
