<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Progress Made On Nazi Compenstation  </HEADLINE>
By PAULINE JELINEK
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- U.S. and German negotiators moved one step
closer Monday to setting up a plan for compensating Nazi-era slave
laborers and protecting German companies from further lawsuits by
survivors.
</P>
<P>
   In a 10-hour negotiating session, they agreed on what had been a
major sticking point -- wording of the statement the U.S. government
will submit to courts to discourage the hearing of further suits.
</P>
<P>
   ''I am very pleased that a major hurdle ... has been overcome,''
President Clinton said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today we are on the verge of a historic agreement,'' Deputy
Treasury Secretary Stuart E. Eizenstat, chief U.S. negotiator, said
at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   German industry and the German government agreed last year to
set up a 10 billion mark ($5 billion) fund to compensate people
forced to work for little or no pay in support of Hitler's war
machine. In exchange, companies wanted protection from lawsuits
mounting in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But the final agreement has been stalled because German business
leaders were dissatisfied with the ''statement of interest'' the
Clinton administration has offered to submit to U.S. courts
whenever such a case is filed.
</P>
<P>
   ''Finally, we have got it,'' the German envoy to the talks, Otto
Lambsdorff, said at the news conference with Eizenstat.
</P>
<P>
   He said it did not provide ''100 percent guarantee'' against
future lawsuits. ''But we have come as close as possible under ...
the legal system of the United States courts,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lambsdorff said he would take it back to Germany with a
recommendation that it be accepted and passed by Parliament into a
law setting up the so-called German Foundation Initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Manfred Gentz, chairman of the German industry fund and chief
financial officer of DaimlerChrysler, agreed and said he would use
it to press more German companies to contribute to the fund. Some
2,000 companies have pledged money, but it doesn't come near to the
$2.5 billion need for industry's share of the fund.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies had said it was pointless to contribute unless
there was a promise they would be free of lawsuits in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it takes out the uncertainty,'' Gentz said of the
document agreed to Monday. ''It will strengthen our argument to win
new participants.''
</P>
<P>
   The foundation, with contributions from German industry and
government is to pay an estimated 2 million former laborers --
mostly Central and Eastern Europeans -- as well as people on whom
medical experiments were performed and some with other
Holocaust-related claims.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-06-12-00 2051 </TRAILER>
