<HEADLINE> Monday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
Chinese Migrants Riot at British Columbia Jail
<TEXT>
<P>
   VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) -- Dozens of Chinese migrants
smashed windows and set fires Monday at the detention facility
where they've been held since arriving illegally in Canada last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon Green, a British Columbia Corrections spokesman, said 49
migrants housed in three dormitories at the Alouette River
Correctional Center in Maple Ridge began to riot around 8 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have sort of an ongoing series of disturbances there,''
Green said. Migrants ''began to smash windows and break toilets and
light small fires.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 82 migrants being housed at the Maple Ridge facility east
of Vancouver, 49 are believed to be participating in the riot.
</P>
<P>
   He said the riot seemed mainly due to the repatriation of other
Chinese migrants who were among the 600 that arrived last summer
aboard four decrepit cargo ships.
------
Chretien Questions Provincial Medicare Claims
</P>
<P>
   WINNIPEG, Manitoba (AP) -- As far as Prime Minister Jean Chretien
is concerned, Ottawa has already restored all the money chopped
from medicare five years ago and need not cough up another $4.2
billion.
</P>
<P>
   ''We argue that the restoration has been done,'' he said Monday
after an hour-long meeting with Manitoba Premier Gary Doer, where
health care was one of the main topics on the table.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you include all the transfers there's $2 billion more
going to the provinces this year than 93-94.''
</P>
<P>
   The premiers made another plea last week for full restoration of
the money chopped from health care five years ago. They reject the
Liberal math and insist $4.2 billion is still owing.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, they calculated that medicare needs a $13-billion
injection over the next five years to keep pace with a growing and
aging population.
------
Quebec Cree Threaten Court Case Unless Referendum Bill Is Changed
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- The Cree of northern Quebec may challenge the
federal government's referendum bill in court unless it's amended
to guarantee aboriginal people a say in negotiations if the country
ever breaks up.
</P>
<P>
   ''If all else fails and Bill C-20 comes into force, we certainly
will look at whatever resources we have,'' Ted Moses, grand chief
of the Cree, told a Senate committee Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We might even consider a constitutional challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   His stand appeared to catch Phil Fontaine, national chief of the
Assembly of First Nations, by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Fontaine, in his own remarks to the committee, agreed the
legislation, which proposes tough federal ground rules for any
future referendum on Quebec separation, should be modified to meet
aboriginal concerns.
</P>
<P>
   But he shied away from talk of a court challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ---
New Federal Funding Designed To Improve Health in Rural Canada
</P>
<P>
   CHESTERVILLE, Ontario (AP) -- Health Minister Allan Rock has
announced $130 million for projects intended to improve health
services and demonstrate new approaches to health care, especially
in rural Canada.
</P>
<P>
   But little if any of the money will go to address the shortage
of doctors and nurses in rural communities, which a Liberal task
force has identified as the top health concern of rural Canadians.
</P>
<P>
   In the report released Monday -- the same day Rock announced the
new funding -- the Liberal rural caucus recommends medical schools
across the country admit more students, especially from rural
areas, to address the shortage.
</P>
<P>
   The caucus, which conducted extensive public hearings,
recommends greater reliance on midwives, paramedics and nurse
practitioners, and more investment in rural infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest chunk of Rock's announced spending is $80 million
for
</P>
<P>
   converting patient records into digital form.
------
Family Income Rebounds in 1998 but Poverty Lingers
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- Belts were tighter through most of the nasty '90s
but average family income hit a 10-year high in 1998, Statistics
Canada said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The strongest yearly hike in a decade pushed the average
after-tax family income to $49,626 -- up 3.7 per cent from 1997
after adjustments for inflation.
</P>
<P>
   After-tax income is earnings plus government benefits such as
tax credits, minus income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   The 1998 figure is the most recent available and indicates
brighter times ahead, say economists.
</P>
<P>
   It's just $819 higher than the pre-recession peak of $48,807 in
1989 and hardly cause to uncork the bubbly.
</P>
</TEXT>
