<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 20:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oldest daughter testifies she found mother's body  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SAN ANTONIO (AP) - The oldest daughter of a slain Florida woman
testified Monday she found her mother's body covered in blood after
returning home from school, and at first thought her mother was
playing a joke.
</P>
<P>
   ''She was covered in blood. I could see that her throat was
slit. There was blood everywhere, everywhere,'' said Stevie
Bellush, the 16-year-old daughter of Sheila Bellush - the mother of
six who was found shot and stabbed to death in 1997. The murder
occurred in the family's Sarasota, Fla., home.
</P>
<P>
   The teen Bellush was the first prosecution witness to testify
against her father, Allen Blackthorne, 45, who has been linked to
the murder of the elder Bellush, who had given birth to
quadruplets.
</P>
<P>
   A two-count federal indictment charges Blackthorne, a South
Texas millionaire, with interstate conspiracy to commit murder for
hire, which carries a mandatory life sentence, and interstate
domestic violence.
</P>
<P>
   The San Antonio trial is expected to last three to five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Stevie Bellush said she was so convinced Bellush ''was playing a
trick on me'' that she hung up on an emergency service dispatcher
after calling 911 because she wanted to go back to reaffirm what
she had seen.
</P>
<P>
   Dispatchers traced the call and rang the teen back.
</P>
<P>
   ''My mother is dead,'' a sobbing Stevie Bellush was heard saying
on the 911 tape. She was 13 at the time.
</P>
<P>
   She discovered the 2-year-old quadruplets wearing their
lifejackets and crawling in their mother's blood. They were in
their lifejackets because there was a pool in the backyard.
</P>
<P>
   Stevie Bellush was composed during her testimony, but at one
point lowered her head and sobbed when she described the police and
ambulance arriving.
</P>
<P>
   She also testified that her parents were locked in a bitter
battle for about 10 years over custody of the two children from
Bellush's marriage to Blackthorne - Stevie and younger sister
Daryl. Stevie Bellush talked about how Blackthorne would describe
his hatred for Bellush and ''he said he wished she was dead.''
</P>
<P>
   The girl, who referred to Blackthorne by his first name, also
talked about how her mother had strict rules, and as a youngster
she wanted to live with Blackthorne. At his house, she testified,
there were no rules, no bedtime and generous gifts of money and
presents.
</P>
<P>
   As she got older, the teen testified she understood how
Blackthorne has hurt her mother.
</P>
<P>
   After separating in 1987 and divorcing afterward, Stevie
Bellush, her sister and mother lived in church-sponsored housing.
Blackthorne frequently failed to provide child support, Stevie
Bellush testified.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Bellush was working two jobs to make ends meet and
losing weight from undue stress, Stevie Bellush said. She and her
second husband, Jamie Bellush, moved to Florida from the San
Antonio area about six weeks before she was killed. He is the
father of the quads. The Bellush family now lives in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Blackthorne was indicted by a federal grand jury in January. A
day later, a Bexar County grand jury returned state charges. The
federal case now underway is the first to go to trial.
</P>
<P>
   A former golfing buddy of Blackthorne - already convicted of
solicitation of capital murder - said he was paid to arrange his
ex-wife's death.
</P>
<P>
   In opening statements Monday, Assistant U.S. Attorney John
Murphy said Blackthorne didn't like to lose and was embittered
because he did not have custody of his two daughters.
</P>
<P>
   Blackthorne is expected to draw upon a wealth of financial
resources in his defense. His legal team reportedly prepped for
their day in court two years before Blackthorne was even indicted.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Rocha, 30, and Samuel Gonzales, 29, were convicted
previously of solicitation of capital murder in the case. Rocha
testified during his trial that Blackthorne, a golfing buddy, asked
him to arrange his ex-wife's death.
</P>
<P>
   Rocha said he enlisted the help of a friend, Gonzales, who
agreed to find someone willing to do the job for $4,000. Jose Luis
Del Toro Jr., 23, Gonzales' cousin, is accused of being the hit
man.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales said Rocha, an accomplished amateur golfer, told him
the money for the hit, like the plan, came from Rocha's frequent
golf and gambling partner, Blackthorne.
</P>
<P>
   Del Toro, a former high school football star in Uvalde, spent 20
months in a Mexican jail after fleeing across the border. He was
extradited last July 12 to face a first-degree murder charge in
Sarasota. His trial is scheduled for next month in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales avoided a trial by pleading guilty to solicitation of
capital murder and agreeing to testify against Rocha. He was
sentenced to 19 years in prison. Rocha was sentenced to life.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
