<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First lady, House Whip share foster care award  </HEADLINE>
By SHANNON McCAFFREY
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) - They are about as odd a political couple as
there is in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But Democrat Hillary Rodham Clinton and Republican House Whip
Tom DeLay shared an award Monday night honoring their work to
improve foster care. Typically at bitter odds with each other,
Clinton and DeLay heaped praise on each other Monday night as they
smiled and posed for pictures together.
</P>
<P>
   ''I guarantee you we are an example that children can bring
anybody together,'' DeLay quipped.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's GOP rival, Rep. Rick Lazio, has questioned whether she
would be effective in working with Capitol Hill Republicans - many
of whom voted to impeach her husband.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady has cited her work with DeLay as evidence that
she can work in a bipartisan fashion. The Texas Republican is one
of the Clinton administration's fiercest critics and a leader in
the impeachment drive. He has also been a foster parent to three
children.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton on Monday night called DeLay ''the whip of all whips''
on foster care legislation.
</P>
<P>
   ''When it came time to persuade people that this needed to be a
priority, he was there day in and day out,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   DeLay noted that many people had referred to him and the first
lady as ''an odd couple.
</P>
<P>
   ''But I do not think it's at all odd that Americans of different
perspectives can come together to meet the solemn obligation our
nation has to those who cannot help themselves.
</P>
<P>
   He added that did not mean he expected to be ''hanging around
the East Wing (of the White House) anytime soon ... reminiscing
about the good old days.''
</P>
<P>
   The award Monday night was given by the non-partisan Orphan
Foundation of America, formed to help older foster children
transition to adulthood.
</P>
<P>
   The Vienna, Va.-based group cited Clinton and DeLay's
longstanding commitment to children, specifically their work on two
key pieces of legislation.
</P>
<P>
   The Adoption and Safe Families Act that passed in 1997 broke
down barriers to adoption. Among other things, it provided
encouragement in the form of cash bonuses to states that increased
the number of adoptions from the foster care system.
</P>
<P>
   The Foster Care Reform Act that passed last year extended
benefits and other assistance for the 20,000 adolescents who ''age
out'' out of foster care each year at age 18.
</P>
<P>
   ''For us it isn't political. It's common sense to care about
these kids,'' Orphan Foundation of America Executive Director
Eileen McCaffrey said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone was so non-partisan. In a television interview
Sunday, Lazio strategist Mike Murphy accused Clinton of ''trying to
create a record for herself in the middle of the campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   After the demise of her sweeping health care reform plan in
1994, Clinton largely retreated from public view but continued to
work on policy. Because that work was done behind the scenes it has
sometimes been difficult for her campaign to establish a specific
record of accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   But at least some Republicans involved in the adoption
legislation recall the first lady's involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's certainly been very supportive and used the bully pulpit
that she has to bring some needed attention to this,'' said Sen.
Mike DeWine, R-Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Benjamin Cardin, D-Md, who worked on last year's foster
care bill, recalled Clinton working the phones in the crucial days
leading up the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ''Especially on children's issues she has tremendous credibility
on both sides of the aisle,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-12-00 2156 </TRAILER>
