<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Monday, June 12, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
S. Korea Leader Arrives for Summit
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- On a mission to end the Cold War on the Korean
Peninsula, South Korean President Kim Dae-jung arrived in North Korea on Tuesday
for a historic summit -- an event that offers the greatest hope for peace on the
divided peninsula in more than 50 years. The South Korean presidential jet
landed at Sunan airport near Pyongyang, the North's capital, after detouring
over the sea during the 70-minute trip from Seoul. There is no direct air travel
between Korea's capitals, and hundreds of thousands of soldiers are deployed on
both sides of the Demilitarized Zone, or DMZ, which separates the North and
South.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Los Alamos Nuclear Secrets Missing
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Two computer hard drives containing an array of nuclear
secrets have disappeared from a highly secured vault at the Los Alamos National
Laboratory in New Mexico, prompting a top-level investigation, laboratory and
Energy Department officials disclosed today. Energy Department officials first
learned that the nuclear secrets and other sensitive material were missing on
June 1 and have not ruled out the possibility that the disappearance is related
to the forest fire that threatened the lab and forced its evacuation last month.
Senior officials expressed doubt that it involved espionage.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Gov't To Compensate Nixon Estate
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Nixon's estate will receive an $18 million
compensation payment from the Justice Department for thousands of secretly
recorded tapes and presidential papers seized when he resigned in 1974. The
government said Nixon's estate at one point had sought $35 million plus 25 years
worth of interest, bringing the asking price to more than $200 million. The $18
million figure was reached in a settlement in U.S. District Court in Washington
over the value of items seized when Nixon resigned rather than face impeachment.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Court Nixes Some Lawsuits vs. HMOs
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court today shut down one legal avenue for
people to sue their health-maintenance organizations. The justices' unanimous
ruling said patients cannot use a federal law to sue HMOs for giving doctors a
financial incentive to cut treatment costs. Such lawsuits could mean the end of
HMOs, which are based on financial incentives, the court said. In another
ruling, the Supreme Court made it easier for employees to prove they were
victims of on-the-job discrimination, or at least get their accusations to a
jury, without direct evidence of intentional bias.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Soldier Suicides Are Rising
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Soldier suicides are on the rise. In hopes of rallying his
troops to confront this sensitive issue, the Army chief of staff has issued an
unusually public -- and deliberately blunt -- call for commanders to take the
offensive. Statistics do not indicate any general increase in suicides for the
military as a whole, although the Army says its suicide rate has gone up the
past two years to one of the highest levels since the 1970s.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Boy Indicted As Adult in Slaying
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) -- A 13-year-old boy accused of shooting a Florida
teacher to death was indicted as an adult today on first-degree murder charges
and he will get life in prison without parole if convicted. Nathaniel Brazill
was charged in the May 26 slaying of Lake Worth Community Middle School teacher
Barry Grunow, who was killed in the closing minutes of the last day of the
school year. It happened after Brazill had been sent home for throwing water
balloons. If prosecuted as a juvenile, he could be held only until he turns 21.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Tokyo Stocks Fall
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks fell early Tuesday with selling centered on
technology issues after a slide on Wall Street. The Nikkei Stock Average shed
136.41 points to 16,844.20 in the first 30 minutes of trading. In New York on
Monday, the Dow industrials ended down 49.85 at 10,564.21. The Nasdaq Composite
Index was down 106.93 at 3,767.91. On the New York Stock Exchange, decliners led
advancers 1,480-1,414.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Yankees, Cubs Mull Sosa Trade
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The Yankees and Chicago Cubs are talking about a Sammy Sosa
trade, and some New York officials think a deal could be made by the All-Star
break. Chicago Cubs scouts have been looking at the Yankees' farm system
recently, and Gene Michael, New York's top scout, has been at Cubs games. Later
this week, Michael is to follow Detroit's Juan Gonzalez, another player the
Yankees want. Sosa, who feuded with Cubs manager Don Baylor last week before
proclaiming peace, has made it clear to Chicago that he wants a trade, three
baseball sources said today, all on the condition they not be identified.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief by MARIA CODER
</SUBHEAD>
