<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brooklyn company recalls dried sweet potatoes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - A Brooklyn company recalled about 10,000 bags of
dried sweet potatoes Monday because the labels failed to mention
that the potatoes contained sulfites.
</P>
<P>
   People who are allergic to sulfites can become seriously ill or
die if they consume them. The sweet potatoes had been distributed
throughout New York state.
</P>
<P>
   Strong America Limited recalled its 7 ounce bags of STR Brand
Dried Sweet Potato after it was discovered that potatoes containing
sulfites were distributed in packages that did not indicate the
presence of sulfites.
</P>
<P>
   The dried sweet potatoes contained 41.96 milligrams of sulfites
per serving, according to the company. Ten milligrams can cause
severe reactions in some asthmatics and other allergic people.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers who purchased the mislabeled sweet potatoes can return
them to the place of purchase for a full refund.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
