<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 22:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gore notes 'irony' in pitching reform while raising campaign cash  </HEADLINE>
By LAURENCE ARNOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Al Gore promoted campaign finance reform at
a Democratic fund-raiser Monday, then hit the trail with Jon
Corzine, the Senate candidate whose $33 million primary bid is this
year's symbol of spending excess.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting next to Gore on a counter stool in a diner, Corzine
maintained an uneasy smile as the Democratic presidential contender
weighed in on the phenomenon of a candidate spending tens of
millions of his own dollars.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's for the voters to decide,'' said Gore. ''There's no
campaign reform bill from any of the reform groups that I've seen
that would have an effect on an individual spending his or her own
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore said the problem is special-interest money in campaigns. He
added that Corzine, a New Jersey Democrat, ''will make a great
United States senator.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Gore spoke at a fund-raiser that brought in $400,000
for the Democratic National Committee - at least some of it in the
unregulated ''soft money'' that he says he will try to outlaw as
president.
</P>
<P>
   Gore will leave Tuesday on a three-week ''progress and
prosperity tour'' to celebrate good economic times and claim at
least partial credit as vice president.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign ridiculed that as ''Al Gore's
I-Invented-Prosperity Tour.'' Spokesman Ari Fleischer said,
''Americans - not government - deserve credit for our nation's
prosperous times.''
</P>
<P>
   Monday night, Gore participated in a 90-minute televised forum
sponsored by Oxygen, the new cable television network developed by
Oprah Winfrey and devoted to women's issues.
</P>
<P>
   The moderator was former White House Deputy Counsel Cheryl
Mills, who played a key role in President Clinton's impeachment
trial. Mills is now Oxygen's senior vice president of corporate
policy and public programing.
</P>
<P>
   Oxygen promoted the event as: ''Al Gore gets in touch with his
feminine side.'' Facing a studio audience of 150 women, Gore
promised more money for special education, pledged his support for
affirmative action and said he does not believe enough doubts have
been raised about capital punishment to warrant a nationwide
moratorium.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also detailed his support for a woman's right to an
abortion and added, for emphasis, that the next president is likely
to appoint enough justices to shape the Supreme Court for 30 to 40
years.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is an issue in the forefront of this year's debate in
this presidential election,'' Gore said, ''and let me just state
clearly again: I support a woman's right to choose. My opponent
does not.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the day, much of the talk was about campaign money.
</P>
<P>
   Corzine, worth an estimated $400 million, relied mostly on his
own money in the record-breaking spending that helped him win last
week's Democratic primary against former Gov. Jim Florio.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Corzine said he shares Gore's support for
campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've said over and over again during this campaign that we
have to open up the airwaves,'' said Corzine, the former chairman
of Wall Street's Goldman Sachs &AMP; Co. ''When people sit down and
look at how we used the resources we had, it was buying media.
Media is very expensive, and if we had not done that, we would not
have been competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   At a late-morning fund-raiser at a private home on Long Island,
Gore acknowledged the irony in raising money and preaching reform
at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   But he said, ''If you entrust me with the presidency, the very
first bill I'll send to the Congress will be the McCain-Feingold
campaign finance reform bill, and then I want to go beyond that to
reform our electoral process and the way campaign money is
raised.''
</P>
<P>
   The McCain-Feingold bill would outlaw soft money raised by
parties. Gore has also proposed creating a $7.1 billion ''Democracy
Endowment'' that would pay for campaigns of candidates who elect
not to accept any political donations.
</P>
<P>
   Previewing his prosperity trip, Gore told the 100 supporters
present, ''Instead of the biggest deficits we now have the biggest
surplus. Instead of a triple-dip recession we've seen a tripling of
the stock market. ... And officially as of two months ago, we now
have the longest economic expansion, the strongest economic
recovery and the healthiest economy in the entire 211-year history
of the American economy. That is a success story.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's trip begins Tuesday with a speech in New York City, then
an address in Pennsylvania on health care. Gore travels to Ohio on
Wednesday to discuss tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican National Committee suggested a better name for
his trip would be the ''Broken Promises Tour.''
</P>
<P>
   New York Gov. George Pataki said Congress and the nation's
governors share credit for prosperous times.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the height of hypocrisy for the man who claims to have
invented the Internet to now claim he's invented prosperity,'' said
Pataki, who leads Texas Gov. George W. Bush's New York presidential
campaign effort.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
