<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 22:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mexican Gunmen Ambush Police Truck  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN CRISTOBAL DE LAS CASAS, Mexico (AP) -- Gunmen ambushed a
group of police as they searched for bandits in southern Mexico on
Monday, killing seven people and injuring two, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Those killed were a state police commander, five state police
officers and a municipal policeman from the nearby mountain village
of Las Limas, about 90 miles north of here. Another police officer
and the son of the town's mayor were injured in the attack,
Attorney General Eduardo Montoya Lievano said.
</P>
<P>
   The group was traveling along a rural highway looking for
bandits responsible for numerous assaults in recent months, Lievano
said. The mayor's son was driving the truck, which was riddled with
more than 80 bullet holes.
</P>
<P>
   Residents in the area are sympathetic to Zapatista rebels in the
southern state of Chiapas. However Lievano said it appears the
Zapatista rebels were not involved and that the assailants were
common criminals.
</P>
<P>
   The Zapatista rebels staged a brief armed uprising in Chiapas in
January 1994, demanding greater democracy and Indian rights. A
partial accord was signed in 1996, but peace talks later broke
down. The Zapatistas have refused to resume negotiations, claiming
the government has failed to abide by the 1996 agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, nine people were killed when the Army tried to
take control of the town of El Bosque, 2 miles) from Las Limas.
Police officers and Zapatista rebels were among the dead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
