<DOCNO> APW20000612.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 22:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White Sox 8, Indians 7  </HEADLINE>
By TOM WITHERS
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND (AP) -- OK, the Chicago White Sox are for real. And get
this, there's finally a real race in the AL Central.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Thomas hit a two-run homer and Ray Durham had three RBIs
Monday night as first-place Chicago opened a three-game lead over
Cleveland with an 8-7 win over the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   If this was supposed to be Chicago's first test this season,
then the White Sox passed. They outhit, outpitched and outlasted
the Indians, the five-time defending division champs.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland got within 8-7 in the ninth on Jim Thome's home run,
but Keith Foulke got Sandy Alomar Jr. to hit into a game-ending
double play.
</P>
<P>
   Cal Eldred (7-2) pitched six effective innings for the White
Sox, who hadn't been in first place during a visit to Jacobs Field
since July 21, 1994. And the way Chicago is playing, it seems the
White Sox are enjoying the view from atop the standings.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago has won 10 of 12 and Monday began a stretch of 14 games
where it will play the Indians seven times, and the World Series
champion New York Yankees seven more.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Branyan homered twice, and Travis Fryman, Kenny Lofton
and Thome connected for the Indians, who have been in first place
just 17 days this season after being there for 360 of a possible
362 days the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Foulke got out of a bases-loaded, one-out jam in the ninth to
get his 15th save. Foulke gave up Thome's 16th homer and Enrique
Wilson followed with an infield single. Foulke then walked Branyan
and Richie Sexson to load the bases before getting Alomar to ground
into a double play to end it.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Paul Rigdon (1-1) took the loss.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing 8-3, the Indians scored twice in the seventh and had
runners at second and third with none out.
</P>
<P>
   But reliever Bob Howry struck out David Justice and Thome before
getting Fryman on a tapper in front of the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Fryman argued that catcher Brook Fordyce fielded the ball in
foul territory and was ejected by plate umpire Chuck Meriwether.
</P>
<P>
   Branyan's second homer -- and sixth in 19 at-bats this season --
brought the Indians within 8-6 in the eighth, and again Cleveland
had runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   But Howry retired Omar Vizquel on a fly to right and struck out
Roberto Alomar with runners at second and third.
</P>
<P>
   Durham's two-run double and Thomas' two-run homer gave the White
Sox a 4-2 lead in the third.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs, Thomas drove a 2-1 pitch from Rigdon 426 feet to
left for his eighth homer in 14 games and 16th this season, one
more than he had all last year.
</P>
<P>
   Fryman's 13th homer brought the Indians within 4-3 in the
fourth, but Durham put the White Sox back up by two in the fifth
with his 10th homer.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago added a run in the sixth on a double-play grounder and
went up 8-3 in the seventh on RBI singles by Thomas and Magglio
Ordonez.
</P>
<P>
   Thome walked to lead off the second and Branyan homered into
Chicago's bullpen in right.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago first baseman Paul Konerko killed a potentially big
inning for the Indians by fielding Lofton's hard smash to start a
3-6-3 double play.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Howry hadn't allowed a run against the Indians in 13 2-3
career innings before Branyan's homer in the eighth. ... Thomas'
homer helped the White Sox tie a club record (1987) by homering in
their 16th straight game. It also tied Thomas with Hall of Famer
George Brett with 317 career homers, 76th on the career list. ...
Roberto Alomar's fiancee, French Open champion Mary Pierce, just
back from winning her title Saturday in Paris, attended the game.
... Alomar said he'll continue to play through the pain in his left
wrist as long as he can. He strained a tendon while making a check
swing in Chicago last month and has been told by doctors that it
will only get better with rest. Alomar, who has been reluctant to
get a cortisone shot, said ''nothing was going to keep me out of
this series.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
