<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Notes From Monday's Baseball Games  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressAMERICAN LEAGUE:
Red Sox-Yankees:
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON: OF Carl Everett, still bitter about his tenure with the
Yankees, challenged their fans. ''They booed everything I did last
time here. That's fine. I just ask them to get more original stuff,
because I like to get involved and laugh. The fans here aren't
nearly as original as the ones in Fayetteville,'' he said. ... For
the second straight game, Jose Offerman started at first base and
Jeff Frye at second. ... Reliever Bryce Florie was scheduled to
make his first appearance for Double-A Trenton after making two
appearances for Single-A Sarasota.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK: Some of the Yankees were intrigued by the possibility
of a day-night, two-stadium doubleheader next month against the
Mets. The most likely scenario being discussed to makeup Sunday's
rainout is to play two on July 8: an afternoon game at Shea Stadium
followed by a night game at Yankee Stadium. ''That's a first for
me,'' manager Joe Torre said. ''But it probably has to happen
because there's no other day we can play it.'' ... 2B Chuck
Knoblauch, out since last Sunday with a sore left forearm, was back
in the lineup hitting leadoff. ''It's the order we want. It's nice
to have him back in the lineup,'' Torre said. ... Next up for the
Yankees is Pedro Martinez, who shut them out May 28. ''You have to
assume that one of these days, we're going to get him,'' Jeter
said.
Athletics-Twins:
</P>
<P>
   OAKLAND: The Athletics have won seven road series this season,
tying their total for the entire 1999 season. ... The A's are using
their 55th different lineup in 63 games. Oakland entered Monday's
game last in batting average (.257) but first in runs scored (366).
</P>
<P>
   MINNESOTA: The Twins acquired minor league RHP Mike Romano from
Toronto in exchange for INF Jimmy Alvarez. Romano was 6-3 with a
3.25 ERA in 10 starts with Triple-A Syracuse. He will be assigned
to Triple-A Salt Lake City.
Mariners-Royals:
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE: RHP Brett Tomko flew back to Seattle to have his
shoulder examined by Dr. Larry Pedegana. Tomko, who was 4-2 with a
5.24 ERA, has tendinitis in his throwing shoulder and was placed on
the 15-day DL. The Mariners are in the middle of their longest road
trip of the year, a 10-game sojourn to San Francisco, Kansas City,
and Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY: The 64-year-old woman who was shot while sitting in
the stands at a Royals game Friday night got a call from team
president and Hall of Fame 3B George Brett. Brett expressed his
personal sympathy and the concern of the team to the woman, who was
not seriously hurt. The woman's seat was facing the 12-story
scoreboard and police have found a bullet hole in the back of the
scoreboard, indicating the shots were fired from outside the
stadium.
Blue Jays-Tigers:
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO: The Blue Jays believe they started the first
all-Castillo battery Monday night when RHP Frank Castillo went to
the mound, with Alberto Castillo behind the plate against Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   DETROIT: 1B Tony Clark, activated Monday from the 15-day
disabled list after recovering from a strained left ribcage, was in
the Tigers' lineup -- batting eighth -- against Toronto. In a
three-game rehab assignment with the Toledo Mud Hens over the
weekend, Clark went 1-for-12. Before the injury, he was hitting
.176 in 25 games for Detroit.
White Sox-Indians
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO: With seven games against the Indians and seven vs. the
New York Yankees in the next 14 days, White Sox manager Jerry
Manuel expects to find out even more about his team. ''This is a
huge series because we are the team being chased,'' Manuel said
before the opener of a three-game set in Cleveland. ''When you're
on top the focus and attention is on you.'' Manuel said it's still
a little different seeing the Sox atop the AL Central standings.
''I couldn't imagine (in spring training) we'd be at this point.
But I was always optimistic.'' ... Through 61 games in 1999, the
White Sox (37-24) were 31-30 and trailed the Indians by nine games.
The last time they came to Cleveland in first place was on July 21,
1994. ... The White Sox entered the biggest series of the season
thus far having won their last five series. It's their longest
series streak since winning five in a row in April of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND: RHP Charles Nagy, who had elbow surgery last month,
threw 65 pitches off a mound Monday. ''He did good,'' pitching
coach Dick Pole said. ''He threw fastballs and changeups and said
there wasn't any distress.'' Before having elbow chips removed May
19, Nagy hadn't missed a start since 1993. He was expected to be
out eight weeks, but is ahead of schedule. ... RF Manny Ramirez's
left hamstring is still hurting and he will not come off the 15-day
DL on Wednesday as scheduled. ''He can run, but it still bothers
him,'' Indians manager Charlie Manuel said. Ramirez may need to go
on a minor league rehab assignment if he's out more than a few
extra days, Manuel said. ... 3B Travis Fryman was forced to play
first base for the first time in his career in Sunday's game
against Cincinnati. ''It was very strange'' said Fryman. ''The game
comes at you from different angles.'' Fryman doesn't own a first
baseman's glove, so he borrowed Jim Thome's backup glove.
NATIONAL LEAGUE:
Marlins-Phillies:
</P>
<P>
   FLORIDA: Cliff Floyd flew back to Miami after being diagnosed
with a contusion sprain of his left knee. Floyd injured the knee in
Sunday's game at Tampa Bay. His status is not yet clear. ... The
Marlins probably aren't too happy to be getting back to playing NL
opponents. In interleague play, Florida is 35-23, tied with
Cleveland for the best record. The Marlins have won 13 of the 20
series they have played vs. the AL.
</P>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA: The 1980 Phillies, the only team to win a World
Series in franchise history, will have its 20th reunion this
weekend. Among the events scheduled are the Richie Ashburn Golf
Outing and an autograph session to benefit ALS. The team will also
be honored in pregame ceremonies at the Vet on Saturday night. On
Friday, an unusual gala concert will be held at Philadelphia's
Academy of Music to honor the team, with performances by Peter Nero
and the Philly Pops mixing with R&AMP;B artists Ashford and Simpson.
Tug McGraw, the closer for that team, will give a rendition of
''Casey at the Bat'' at the gala ... RHP Curt Schilling threw
batting practice to three teammates before the game in an attempt
to ''work things out.'' Schilling is 1-4 this season with a 6.34
ERA since coming off the disabled list. ... The Phillies' winning
percentage against the Florida Marlins is the highest than against
any other opponent.
Brewers-Expos:
</P>
<P>
   MILWAUKEE: Dave Krynzel, Milwaukee's first-round pick in last
week's draft, signed his contract Monday morning at County Stadium.
Despite rain, the CF from Green Valley High School in Henderson,
Nev., hit in the cages underneath the stadium. Soon he will go to
Ogden, Utah, to participate in the Brewers' rookie camp. ... C
Henry Blanco remained in Venezuela to attend the funeral of his
father, Carlos, who died Saturday night. Blanco is expected to
return Wednesday. ... Eight players from the team's Class-A Midwest
League representative, the Beloit, Wis., Snappers, have been placed
on the Western Division All-Star team.
</P>
<P>
   MONTREAL: Four Expos -- Vladimir Guerrero, Lee Stevens, Jose
Vidro and Rondell White -- are on pace to drive in 120 runs. There
have never been even two Expos to drive in more than 100 runs in
the same year. ... Four Expos pitchers on the DL progressed in
their rehabilitation Monday. Scott Strickland and Matt Blank flew
to Jupiter, Fla., to continue their work. Mike Thurman threw soft
toss for the first time since late May. Reliever Ugueth Urbina
started long-toss throwing after undergoing arthroscopic surgery on
May 17 to remove a bone chip in his right elbow. ... Stevens was a
late scratch from Monday's game after straining his right hamstring
Sunday against Toronto. His status will be evaluated daily.
Braves-Pirates:
</P>
<P>
   ATLANTA: Greg Maddux, who starts Wednesday, is 8-0 -- allowing 15
earned runs in 12 starts -- since last losing to the Pirates on
April 30, 1994. ... John Burkett, an all-state pitcher at Beaver
High School near Pittsburgh in the mid-1980s, starts Tuesday. He is
3-4 with a 6.64 ERA at Three Rivers Stadium and 7-4 in his career
against Pittsburgh. The Braves visit Pittsburgh only once this
season, so this will likely be Burkett's final start in the stadium
where he grew up watching games. ... Braves SS Rafael Furcal limped
into second base on a first-inning double Monday, but stayed in
after being examined by a trainer. However, he was lifted in the
second for a pinch-hitter. ... Bobby Bonilla was scratched for the
second day in a row with an illness. He has seven hits in 17
at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   PIITSBURGH: RHP Jason Schmidt, who has had shoulder problems
since spring training, was placed on the disabled list Monday for
the second time this season. He will be examined Wednesday in
Birmingham, Ala., by James Andrews. ... RHP Bronson Arroyo, 22-8 in
the minors the last two season, was recalled from Triple-A
Nashville and will make his major league debut Tuesday against the
Braves. ... The Pirates have lost eight of their last 10 road
games. ... Brian Giles had 60 RBIs in the Pirates' first 60 games
and is on pace to drive in a club-record 162 runs. Willie Stargell
had 67 RBIs in 60 games during the Pirates' World Series
championship season in 1971 before finishing with 125 RBIs. ...
J.R. House, a catcher who set numerous national high school
football passing records at Nitro (W.Va.) High in 1998, is batting
.361 at Class A Hickory.
Cardinals-Padres:
</P>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS: OF Ray Lankford was held out of the lineup one day
after he sprained his right hand while striking out against
Detroit. Lankford, the DH against the Tigers, has not started in
the field since June 3 due to a sore left hamstring. ... The last
time the Cardinals were in first place with 100 games left in the
season was in 1987, when they went to the World Series. ... 1B Mark
McGwire has hit seven homers with 19 RBIs in 11 previous games at
Qualcomm Stadium. ... Darryl Kile will attempt to become the
majors' third 10-game winner when he starts Tuesday. Kile won only
eight games last season for Colorado. ... The Cardinals continue to
be the best draw on the road, averaging 35,566 fans in 29 dates.
</P>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO: The Padres are 4-18 (.182) against baseball's
division leaders, including 0-3 against St. Louis. Their mark
against the rest of the division leaders: Atlanta (1-5), Arizona
(3-7) and Oakland (0-3). The Padres are 23-16 (.589) against all
other opponents. ... Tony Gwynn did not start in right field as
part of his routine of not playing in back-to-back games. The
team's medical staff hopes that will help heal Gwynn's ailing left
knee. ... Nine different pitchers have started for the Padres, one
more than the entire 1999 season.
Reds-Giants:
</P>
<P>
   CINCINNATI: RHP Osvaldo Fernandez was originally signed by the
San Francisco Giants, but after missing more than two years due to
reconstructive elbow surgery, he was cut loose. The Reds signed him
as a free agent and he is 2-0 in five games with a 2.76 ERA. He's
scheduled to pitch Tuesday against the Giants. ''You have to cut
the cord sometime,'' Giants manager Dusty Baker said. ''We fixed
him, but sometimes a change of scenery is good. It's good to see
him back in the big leagues.'' ... RF Dante Bichette was not in the
starting lineup Monday after leaving Sunday's game against the
Indians with a mildly sprained left ankle. He's listed as
day-to-day. ... C Eddie Taubensee's streak of consecutive games
without an RBI reached 24 games (84 at-bats) on Sunday (June 11).
... OF Ken Griffey, Jr. will be spending Thursday's off day in
Pebble Beach for the U.S. Open.
</P>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO: SS Rich Aurilia, who strained his left hamstring
on May 30, wasn't in the starting lineup for a second straight day.
Giants manager Dusty Baker said Aurilia will probably take Tuesday
off as well. ''He's feeling OK, but we want to get him two or three
days so he can get back to 100 percent,'' Baker said. ''We don't
want him chronically pulling something.'' ... OF Ellis Burks has a
say in whether he's going to play on a given day. ''It's his call
each day he comes into the locker room,'' said Giants head trainer
Stan Conte. ''It's been the same since spring training, he's
literally day to day.'' ... The Giants haven't lost two consecutive
home games since losing six straight to open Pac Bell Park.
Diamondbacks-Dodgers:
</P>
<P>
   ARIZONA: Luis Gonzalez, NL player of the week, was 24-for-61
against the four pitchers starting for the Dodgers in the four-game
NL West showdown that began Monday night -- Darren Dreifort
(1-for-6), Chan Ho Park (9-for-21), Carlos Perez (3-for-5) and
Kevin Brown (11-for-29). ... Randy Johnson and Todd Stottlemyre
have a combined record of 18-4. The rest of the staff was 19-21.
... Mike Morgan, a starter for most of his 20-year career, is
5-for-5 in save situations after recording his previous save in
1991. The 40-year-old right-hander, who will make his second start
of the season on Tuesday, has played for 12 major league teams and
nine minor league clubs. ... Arizona scored 26 runs in the first
two games of their three-game sweep of the Dodgers last month in
Phoenix, before Brown and Randy Johnson dueled on even terms
without a decision in a game the Diamondbacks won 2-1. But there
won't be a Brown-Johnson rematch this time because Johnson is
pitching Wednesday and Brown is going Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES: Bullpen coach Rick Dempsey was amused by the
videotape of Robin Ventura -- disguised as Mike Piazza -- running
around the bases and splashing into second base during Sunday
night's Mets-Yankees rain delay at Yankee Stadium. It was
reminiscent of Dempsey's waterlogged belly-flopping jaunt around
the bases at Fenway Park some 20 years ago. ''I'd give him an
8.5,'' Dempsey said with a grin. ''He might have to work on it a
few more times, but I had a little more experience than he had. I
got to do it about three or four times, and that was his first try.
But I'm glad that somebody else is picking up the ball and running
with it.'' ... The Dodgers, who drew 3 million fans at home nine
times before any other team did it once, became the ninth of 16 NL
teams the season to reach the one million mark. One reason for the
early dropoff in attendance might be the Lakers, who have played
nine televised NBA playoff games while the Dodgers were at Chavez
Ravine.
</P>
