<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Columbia Swimmer Gets Honda Award  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. (AP) -- Columbia's Cristina Teuscher, the NCAA
swimming champion whose times in the 400-meter freestyle and
individual medley were the second-fastest in the world this year,
won the Honda-Broderick Cup as the nation's outstanding collegiate
woman athlete.
</P>
<P>
   Teuscher was honored Monday night at the 24th annual Collegiate
Woman Athlete of the Year dinner. She was selected by a national
vote involving more than 900 NCAA-member schools.
</P>
<P>
   The senior from New Rochelle, N.Y., was undefeated in nine meets
this season, and never lost an individual race during her college
career.
</P>
<P>
   ''What a way to top off a college career,'' Teuscher said. ''I'm
so happy I could share this with Columbia University. I think this
is probably the most prestigious award I've ever received.''
</P>
<P>
   Teuscher won an Olympic gold medal in the 800-meter relay at the
1996 Atlanta Games and is in training for the Sydney Games in
September.
</P>
<P>
   ''Swimming and academics are in the same realm and it's great to
combine academics and athletics because I never put one in front of
the other,'' she said. ''Swimming and college have matured me. I
feel much better prepared heading into these (Olympic) trials.''
</P>
<P>
   She was the Ivy League champion in the 200- and 400-meter
individual medley, as well as the 100 freestyle, in which she set a
school record. Teuscher also was the Outstanding Swimmer of the Ivy
League Championships for the fourth consecutive year, and holds 10
of 14 school individual records and four relay team records.
</P>
<P>
   In winning the Honda-Broderick Cup, she was selected over 11
other candidates, who were voted best in their respective sports
for 1999-00.
</P>
<P>
   They are: Jen Adams, lacrosse, Maryland; Courtney Blades,
softball, Southern Mississippi; Heather Brink, gymnastics,
Nebraska; Lauren Cacciamani, volleyball, Penn State; Jenna Daniels,
golf, Arizona; Lorrie Fair, soccer, North Carolina; Marissa Irvin,
tennis, Stanford; Sally Northcroft, field hockey, Ball State; Shea
Ralph, basketball, Connecticut; Keisha Spencer, track and field,
Louisiana State; and Amy Yoder, cross-country, Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Basketball player Jayne Even of North Dakota State was honored
as the Division II Woman Athlete of the Year and Alia Fischer, who
played basketball for Washington University in St. Louis, was the
Division III winner.
</P>
<P>
   Distance runner Johanna Olson of Luther College in Decorah,
Iowa, won the Honda Inspiration Award for twice battling back from
a brain tumor to return to competition and win All-America honors.
</P>
<P>
   The Honda-Broderick Cup is the top honor given women college
athletes and is part of a year-long Honda Awards program to
recognize outstanding achievements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
