<HEADLINE> NJ man seeks legal advice from Cochran at airport, ends up at police station </HEADLINE>
By BECKY BOHRER
<TEXT>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) - A man wanted for kidnapping in New
Jersey sought legal advice from Johnnie Cochran and another
attorney during a chance encounter at the airport Monday and ended
up turning himself in at the police station.
</P>
<P>
   James Allan, 39, is accused of kidnapping a former girlfriend
from a grocery store parking lot in Wayne, N.J., on Friday, Police
Sgt. Bruce Elrod said.
</P>
<P>
   Allan drove Linda Gazda, 51, to Des Moines. He told her he
wanted to take her to Las Vegas to get married, and the two went to
the airport Monday afternoon to catch a flight to Nevada, Elrod
said.
</P>
<P>
   At the airport, Allan recognized Cochran, who had been in town
briefly for a news conference. He walked up and spoke with Cochran
and Des Moines attorney Bob Wright Jr., who are working together on
a case.
</P>
<P>
   ''Johnnie told me, 'Look, this could be a prospective client and
he may need help,''' Wright said.
</P>
<P>
   Allan told the lawyers there was a warrant out for his arrest
but that Gazda, whom he allegedly had kidnapped, was with him
voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   ''She's standing behind him and she's mouthing, 'No,''' Wright
said. ''I didn't know what to think of it; she was doing this
rather calmly.''
</P>
<P>
   Wright said Allan let him talk to Gazda, and she said she did
not want to be there. Wright persuaded Allan to follow him to the
police station.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think this gentleman really thought I'd take care of the
warrant for him,'' Wright said. ''I couldn't represent him anyway.
I'm a witness now.''
</P>
<P>
   Police and the FBI were interviewing Gazda on Monday evening,
Elrod said.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Police Lt. John Reardon said Gazda and Allan lived
together briefly until she obtained a temporary restraining order
against him on June 1.
</P>
<P>
   ''She was in great fear of him,'' Reardon said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday evening, Gazda and her 86-year-old mother were
shopping at an A&AMP;P when the mother saw Gazda's car speeding away.
She was left on the curb with the groceries wondering what had
happened, Reardon said.
</P>
<P>
   Gazda managed to call her family several times before police
were able to track the couple through ATM and credit card receipts
to Buffalo, N.Y., early Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Gazda slipped a note to a woman in the ladies' room
of a Chicago restaurant, asking her to call her sister in New
Jersey. The note said ''that her life depended on it,'' Reardon
said. The sister called police, but it was too late.
</P>
<P>
   Gazda is expected to return to New Jersey on Tuesday morning,
Reardon said.
</P>
<P>
   The warrant also charged Allan with violating the restraining
order, which was made permanent on Thursday or Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Cochran and Wright filed a wrongful death lawsuit Monday on
behalf of the family of Charles Lovelady, who died in February
during a fight with two bouncers at a nightclub where he'd been
turned away for a dress code violation.
</P>
<P>
   Associated Press Writer Susan Stocum contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-12-00 2306 </TRAILER>
