<HEADLINE> Vikings' Moss Kicked Off Flight  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN RA
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) -- Minnesota Vikings wide receiver Randy
Moss was kicked off an airplane Monday night after a confrontation
with a flight attendant over the storage of carry-on luggage.
</P>
<P>
   The Pittsburgh-bound US Airways flight had taxied across the
tarmac but returned to the gate at Yeager Airport to have Moss
removed. The matter was turned over to the Federal Aviation
Administration and the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   The confrontation ''was all verbal. Nothing physical,'' said
assistant airport director Dave Sweeney.
</P>
<P>
   A statement released by Moss' agent, Dante diTrapano, called the
incident ''very unfortunate'' and it was ''blown way out of
proportion.''
</P>
<P>
   The statement said Moss boarded the plane with the same luggage
he routinely carries on board.
</P>
<P>
   A flight attendant told Moss the bag was too big and had to be
checked. Trying to avoid waiting at baggage claim on arrival, Moss
removed some clothes and placed them in the overhead compartment,
then placed his bag underneath his seat, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   The flight attendant apparently complained to the captain that
Moss had not followed her instructions, and the captain asked Moss
to leave the plane.
</P>
<P>
   Moss, a former all-America at Marshall, was not immediately
available for comment. A native of nearby Rand, Moss left the
airport after giving a statement to police.
</P>
<P>
   A telephone message left with a spokesman for US Airways wasn't
immediately returned Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The incident was the lead story on all three of Charleston's 11
p.m. television newscasts.
</P>
<P>
   Moss hasn't exactly been the darling of his home state in recent
years. He has been a target of contempt ever since he criticized
West Virginia in several 1998 interviews and said he was happy to
get out of the state.
</P>
<P>
   In November, he was fined $10,000 for excessive verbal abuse of
an NFL official in a game. In January, he was fined $25,000 for
squirting water at an official during an NFC divisional playoff
game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
