<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton, Dole Attend Dodd Party  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- President Clinton was the headliner at a party
in honor of Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., on Monday night, but
his old rival Bob Dole stole the show with a playful surprise
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   The former Senate Republican leader, who lost to Clinton in
1996, poked fun at Democrats, the president and himself in a series
of one-liners that kept the audience of about 600 in stitches.
</P>
<P>
   Dole, who has been a spokesman for the anti-impotence drug
Viagra, joked that it's tough to get work since his unsuccessful
presidential campaign, so he keeps busy with speaking engagements
and commercials.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm told a Viagra side effect for some men in their 50s is
that their hair turns gray,'' he said, a shot at the silver-haired
Dodd, who was celebrating 25 years of public service in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton used his speech to compliment Dodd on his
accomplishments over the years, but also noted Dole's new career in
advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ''He owes me a lot, Bob Dole,'' Clinton said. ''I mean, if it
weren't for me, he'd be just like all us gray-haired 50-year-olds.
He'd have to pay for his Viagra.''
</P>
<P>
   Dole and Dodd were often at odds over legislation in the Senate,
but Dole said he spoke at the $1 million fund-raiser because he
recognizes there is a time for campaigning and a time for working
together.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm proud to call him my friend and I wish him many more years
in the Senate,'' he said. ''All, of course, in the minority.''
</P>
</TEXT>
