<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drug Traffickers Threaten Stability  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SCHUSLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORT-OF-SPAIN, Trinidad (AP) -- Drug traffickers are endangering
democracy in small nations and leaving a trail of violence across
the Americas, speakers told a major anti-drug conference Monday
attended by Attorney General Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the international community does not work together against
drug traffickers, this region's stability and the economic
stability of the world are at grave risk,'' Trinidad's Attorney
General Ramesh Maharaj said.
</P>
<P>
   The two-day conference in Trinidad's capital, aimed at
overcoming international obstacles to law enforcement, brought more
than 100 law enforcement officials from the Caribbean, Britain,
Canada and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   During a tour of a drug rehabilitation center in rural Trinidad
Monday, Reno also urged more cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   ''Boundaries mean less when it comes to crime,'' she said. ''We
are going to have to join together ... to talk about how we can be
partners, large and small, but all equally important in dealing
with the issues of crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Maharaj called drug trafficking ''the greatest threat to
democracy in the region,'' noting U.N. estimates that the illegal
drug trade generates $500 billion a year, more than the world's oil
and gas industries combined.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday night, Reno and Trinidadian officials signed an
agreement setting ground rules for the deportation of Trinidadian
nationals imprisoned in the United States. Such deportations are a
touchy issue with many Caribbean countries, who claim they are
being flooded with U.S.-trained criminals.
</P>
<P>
   Under the pact, the United States promised to better identify
deportees and the charges against them, while Trinidad agreed to
issue travel papers within five working days for convicts who had
documents identifying them as Trinidadian nationals. Those without
proof of Trinidadian citizenship would get papers within 30 days
after an investigation into their nationality.
</P>
<P>
   The United States also promised to send deportees back on
commercial flights instead of charters when possible. Many
countries complain that the unscheduled charter planes dump
deportees on them without warning.
</P>
<P>
   Caribbean countries are also under pressure to loosen secretive
banking laws, which U.S. and European drug agents have said attract
the fortunes of drug barons.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty of balancing anti-drug operations and
international relations was underscored last week, when U.S. drug
agents lured a suspected trafficker out of St. Kitts on a boat in
order to arrest him in international waters.
</P>
<P>
   ''Smugglers don't pay attention to international borders, but
law enforcement has to, not only in tracking them down, but also in
taking action against them,'' said Jay Carmichael, chief counsel
for the U.S. Coast Guard.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the two-day meeting were scheduled to discuss money
laundering, street gangs, how to fight organized crime and
extradition. They were also to consider proposals for specialized
''drug courts'' to speed trials.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
