<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-12 23:58 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Hillary Clinton-Lazio race tight, and a different contest  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - A fourth statewide poll in less than three
weeks has found Hillary Rodham Clinton in a close race in New York
with her new Republican opponent for the U.S. Senate, Rep. Rick
Lazio, and a very different contest.
</P>
<P>
   The CBS News/New York Times poll out Monday had Clinton with a
very slight lead over the little-known congressman from Long
Island. Clinton was backed by 44 percent of likely voters surveyed
to 39 percent for Lazio. Seventeen percent were undecided.
</P>
<P>
   A CBS News/New York Times poll out in April had Clinton leading
Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, 49 percent to 41 percent, with 10 percent
undecided. Giuliani quit the race May 19 to deal with his prostate
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The poll found that in many ways the Senate race has become a
whole new contest with Lazio replacing Giuliani on the Republican
side.
</P>
<P>
   Not only have the number of undecided voters increased, but
while Clinton and Giuliani were running even in traditionally more
conservative upstate New York in April, the new poll had Lazio
leading in that region, 46 percent to 35 percent, in the new poll.
</P>
<P>
   And in the category of who would be better at working with other
senators, Clinton's edge has largely evaporated. In April, Clinton
led Giuliani, 57 percent to 30 percent, on that front. In the new
poll, 42 percent said Clinton would work better with other senators
while 38 percent said that about Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   And while 30 percent of voters said Lazio was spending more time
attacking Clinton than talking about issues, 52 percent said that
was the case with Giuliani back in April.
</P>
<P>
   One thing that hasn't changed is that many New Yorkers would
prefer to have a senator who was born in the state. Almost four in
10 voters in the new poll felt that way. Lazio has been stressing
the carpetbagger issue, presenting himself as the ''Made in New
York'' candidate. Until January, Clinton has never lived in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   But the poll also found that many voters really don't know much
about the new Republican candidate. Forty-seven percent said they
didn't know enough about Lazio to even decide if their impression
of him was favorable or unfavorable. Twenty-six percent said they
had a favorable opinion of him while 10 percent said they had an
unfavorable opinion of the congressman.
</P>
<P>
   The new telephone poll of 1,187 likely voters was conducted June
4-10 and has a margin of error of plus of minus 3 percentage
points.
</P>
<P>
   Other recent polls have also shown the race to be close.
</P>
<P>
   On May 25, the Zogby International Group had the race a
statistical dead heat with Clinton at 46 percent and Lazio at 44
percent.
</P>
<P>
   On June 4, a poll conducted by Blum &AMP; Weprin for the New York
Daily News and cable television's New York 1 all-news channel
reported Clinton with a slight, 46 percent to 42 percent, lead over
Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   On June 7, the Quinnipiac University Polling Institute had
Clinton and Lazio tied, at 44 percent each.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-06-12-00 2358 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
